<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Finance Minister Survives No Confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel
survived an opposition-proposed no confidence vote in parliament
today, with a deal with the country's central bank Bundesbank on
gold and US dollar reserves revaluation still pending.
</P>
<P>
Waigel received 328 votes in favor of his remaining in office,
compared to 311 against.
</P>
<P>
The vote came after Chancellor Helmut Kohl made a long
statement defending him, who last month proposed a bill to raise
the book value of the Bundesbank's 95 million fine ounces of gold
to 60 percent of the current market price from the 25 percent at
present.
</P>
<P>
Waigel's plan has pulled the government and the Bundesbank in a
bitter standoff. The German finance minister has been battling to
fill a budget gap of up to 29 billion marks (16.82 billion US
dollars) this year and at least 15 billion marks (8.7 billion
dollars) in 1998 to qualify Germany for the European single
currency, the euro, which was planned to be launched from 1999.
</P>
<P>
Kohl in the statement today warned that the delay of the euro
would lead to Deutschmark appreciation, thus hindering economic
growth and aggravating the country's record unemployment. He vowed
to do everything to meet the strict budget deficit and debt limits
needed to make Germany one of the first euro member countries in
1999.
</P>
<P>
Germany has failed to meet the criteria in recent years and
most analysts believe it will fail again this year. The main
opposition Social Democrats (SPD) called for delaying euro
introduction. Opinion polls showed two-thirds of German people
were against giving up mark for euro.
</P>
<P>
Waigel's gold revaluation plan could yield a 20 billion mark
(11.6 billion dollar) windfall for the government. However, the
Bundesbank intended to begin paying extra gold revenue to Bonn
from 1999, instead of 1997 as initially demanded by Bonn, nor 1998
as Waigel said he now wanted.
</P>
<P>
Would gold proceeds transfer to Bonn not start from 1997, the
gold revaluation plan would do little help to Bonn in its battle
for joining the euro in 1999.
</P>
<P>
While admitting an accord with the Bundesbank was still
pending, Waigel said earlier today that he would raise new revenue
by speeding up share sales of the state-owned Telecom company and
impose a spending freeze in a bid to ease the budget pressure this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
