<HEADLINE> Blair: Britain Unlikely to Join EMU in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said today that Britain would probably not be among the first wave
of countries joining European Monetary Union (EMU), which is
scheduled for 1999.
</P>
<P>
"We must keep our options open," he told the Commons. It would
be better for EMU not to go ahead at all than for it to start with
"fudged" convergence criteria, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is highly unlikely that Britain would want to join the
first wave of monetary union," he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Chancellor Gordon Brown said the government's
position on a single European currency was unchanged. It would
maintain its "wait-and-see" stance while acknowledging there were
big obstacles to joining in the first round, he said.
</P>
<P>
Instead, Brown unveiled a new employment plan for Europe,
promising to make it a central theme of London's presidency of the
European Union next year.
</P>
<P>
His three-point plan aims to cut unemployment and increase
employment opportunities and labor market flexibility across
Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
