<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, June 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE -- The 33rd summit of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) concluded here Wednesday after adopting a series of
decisions that set the guidelines for promoting peace and economic
development in Africa.
</P>
<P>
BONN -- German Finance Minister Theo Waigel survived an
opposition-proposed no confidence vote in parliament Wednesday,
with a deal with the country's central bank Bundesbank on gold and
U.S. dollar reserves revaluation still pending.
</P>
<P>
Waigel received 328 votes in favor of his remaining in office,
compared to 311 against.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Wednesday that
he hoped the current crisis in Sierra Leone could be resolved by
negotiations, but he refused to rule out a military intervention
in the conflict-stricken West African country.
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italy is to send more troops to Albania ahead of the
June 29 general election in the Balkan country to protect polling
stations, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But he said the exact number of the reinforcement troops has
yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
CANBERRA -- Australia's annual economic growth has slowed down
to 2.4 percent for the 1996-97 fiscal year despite an improved
performance in the first three months of 1997, the Australian
Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said in a report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The growth was found to be 3.2 percent in a previous survey
conducted by the ABS. 
