<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Presents Plan On Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu presented today his plan on the Israeli-Palestinian
final settlement, which was immediately rejected by the Palestinian
side.
</P>
<P>
The plan, in which Netanyahu envisions retaining strategic
borders, settlements, water resources and key roads, was presented
to the inner cabinet in its second meeting in the past days to
discuss arrangements for the final-status talks with the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
The inner cabinet, which includes Foreign Minister David Levy
and Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, discussed the issue for
the first time last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Netanyahu's plan, Israel will keep most of the
Jewish settlements scattered in the Palestinian territories of
West Bank and Gaza Strip. It will also retain control over
the Jordan River, strategic borders in the Jordan Valley.
</P>
<P>
Israel will build a Greater Jerusalem whose boundaries are
to be extended in all directions: to Maaleh Adumim settlement
in the east and to Gush Etzion settlement in the south.
The Jerusalem Corridor under Israeli control will link Greater
Jerusalem westward to the coastal plain in the west.
</P>
<P>
In general, Israel intends to create security belts in
areas along the Green Line, or the border until the 1967
war.
</P>
<P>
But the Prime Minister's Office said Israel was not
committed to any map on the final arrangements, and the plan
presented by Netanyahu was neither an opening nor a closing
position in future final-status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The plan is almost identical to the detailed map published
by Hebrew dailies last Thursday, which marked the borders,
roads and settlements that will be under Israeli control in
the final settlement. The map showed that the PNA will get
about 40 percent of the territories, much less than the 90
percent it has required.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu apparently formulated the plan after taking into
consideration of the security map presented to the first inner
cabinet meeting by the security establishment, which recommended
retaining control over all the strategic areas in the
territories.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to coalition lawmakers Tuesday in the Knesset
(Parliament), Netanyahu said he believed that his government
would reach a final settlement with the PNA. He added such
agreement would be a package deal which the public would be
able to unite behind.
</P>
<P>
Despite the current difficulties in the Israeli-Palestinian
peace process, Netanyahu said the final-status talks could be
resumed in the near future. The peace talks have been
deadlocked since Israel began building the controversial Har
Homa settlement in East Jerusalem late March.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Israel would not allow the redivision of
Jerusalem, not return to the 1967 borders and not agree to
the influx of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Following the inner cabinet discussion, Netanyahu said he
would bring his plan for the final settlement to the full
cabinet and the Knesset for debate and approval.
</P>
<P>
As before, the Palestinian side swiftly rejected the
Netanyahu plan on the final settlement. Ahmed Tibi, adviser to
PNA President Yasser Arafat, said the plan was a non-starter,
because it did not represent peace but confrontation. He said
Israel would never succeed in imposing conditions on the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The PNA is hoping to establish an independent Palestinian
state on the most of West Bank and Gaza Strip with East
Jerusalem as its capital in the final settlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0020 </DOCNO>
