<HEADLINE> Lebanon Protests Israel over Civilian Casualties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon lodged today a complaint to
an international panel monitoring cease-fire in south Lebanon over
civilian casualties in mine blasts in the Western Beqaa, Beirut
Foreign Ministry sources said.
</P>
<P>
In the complaint, Lebanon accused the Israeli occupation
forces of targeting civilians, thus violating a cease-fire
understanding the two sides reached in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
South Lebanese security sources reported that four mines,
planted by the Israelis on the main road between the towns of
Zilaya and Qalya near the edge of the Israeli self-proclaimed
"security zone", exploded as a civilian pickup was passing by.
</P>
<P>
The blasts, which took place at 9:30 a.m. (0630 GMT), led to
the killing of the driver and the injury of two passengers.
</P>
<P>
Police suspected that the mines were detonated by remote
control, according to the anonymous security sources.
</P>
<P>
The monitoring committee, set up following a 17-day Israeli
blitz in south Lebanon in April 1996 and on the basis of the
cease-fire understanding to comprise representatives from France,
Israel, Lebanon, Syria and the United States, was to look into
complaints over cease-fire violations.
</P>
<P>
Mediated by the U.S. and France, the cease-fire understanding
bars the fighting sides from targeting civilians or launching
operations from civilian areas.
</P>
<P>
Israeli occupation forces fired heavy artilleries sporadically
at no-man's areas opposite the buffer zone over the night
and during the daytime without causing casualties.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese resistance guerrillas fired back with mortar shells.
</P>
<P>
The two sides' trading fire constitutes a daily scene in
south Lebanon, the last active battlefront of the Arab-Israeli
conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
