<HEADLINE> Turco-Greek Odds Should Be Solved Peacefully: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Former Greek Prime Minister
Konstantin Mitsotakis said today that the existing problems
between Turkey and Greece should be solved peacefully and through
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
According to the semi-official Anatolia News Agency, Mitsotakis
made this remark in his meeting today with Turkish Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) Chairman Besim Tibuk in Istanbul, the
largest city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Mitsotakis, who was awarded Abdi Ipekci Friendship and Peace
Special Prize in the city, said that the relations between
neighboring Turkey and Greece should be improved.
</P>
<P>
"There is not a concrete possibility of war at the moment, yet
the governments of the two countries should officially declare
that there is not a possibility of war," he said.
</P>
<P>
Abdi Ipekci Friendship and Peace Prize was founded to
commemmorate the outstanding Turkish journalist who was
assassinated in 1979 and to keep alive his efforts for Turco-Greek
friendship.
</P>
<P>
On the Cyprus issue, Mitsotakis said: "This problem should
be solved soon. Peace will be for the benefit of all sides."
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both NATO members, have long been at odds
over a number of issues including the limits of air space, mineral
rights below the Aegean Sea and the Cyprus issue. 
</P>
