<HEADLINE> McDonald's Gives Up 55-Cent Sandwiches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The McDonald's Corporation
announced late Tuesday that it was canceling all lunch and dinner
promotions built around discounting sandwiches to 55 cents under
the pressure from among its franchisees.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times reported today that the announcement
signaled unusual disarray in the marketing plans of McDonald's,
the world's leader in fast food. Just last week, the company
confirmed that it would not begin a program to offer free food to
diners who had not been served within 55 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The promotion made its debut with Big Mac hamburgers being sold
for 55 cents along with any order of fries and a drink. In late
May, the quarter-pound cheeseburger replaced the Big Mac.
</P>
<P>
But many consumers found it difficult to get the 55-cent
hamburger and were disappointed that the savings were often minor
compared with other value packages on the menu of McDonald's
competitors.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, many franchisees said the promotion was not
generating enough new business to cover the costs. The package was
a money-loser for them.
</P>
<P>
Still the new announcement surprised some franchisees who had
been among the company's harshest critics in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
McDonald's reported recently that sales at restaurants opened
at least a year rose in the first quarter of this year. It said
that today's cancellation was "a midcourse correction" in Campaign
55, which would continue in the form of breakfast My Size meals,
which offer various combinations of food built around the 55-cent
theme. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
