<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Gears up for Fight Against Malaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
HARARE, June 4 (Xinhua) -- African leaders today reaffirmed
their "unflagging resolve" to prevent the outbreak of malaria which
claims 4,200 lives every day on the continent.
</P>
<P>
The leaders, ending their 33rd summit here, issued a declaration
which considers malaria control in Africa as one of the continent's
priority programs.
</P>
<P>
The declaration said African countries "support fully the
implementation of the Global and Regional Strategy and approaches
recommended by the World Health Organization."
</P>
<P>
African countries, the declaration said, will implement well
planned and coordinated malaria control programs involving
individuals, families, communities, institutions, relevant
government ministries, and other public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
The declaration called on African countries to allocate
sufficient human, financial and material resources, and mobilize
other local resources including resources from non-governmental and
private and civil sectors, for the sustained prevention and control
of malaria in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Efforts should also be made to mobilize additional external
resources from international agencies, governmental and
non-governmental agencies, foundations and industrial and commercial
enterprises to support national and commercial action to control
malaria and surveillance to prevent epidemics and sustain the
progress already made, the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
It suggested the following actions:
</P>
<P>
-- Give full political support to actions directed towards
sustainable malaria preventioan and control as an urgent priority;
</P>
<P>
-- Further develop and implement plans for malaria prevention
and control, including incorporation into development projects based
on environmental and health impact assessments;
</P>
<P>
-- Develop strong community based programs to mobilize active
community participation for malaria prevention and control;
</P>
<P>
-- Promote and support micro-financing schemes, especially for
women, to initiate income generating projects aimed at basic
environmental and household improvements;
</P>
<P>
-- Develop mechanisms that will facilitate and ensure well
coordinated multisectoral action to reduce substantially the burden
of malaria and promote inter-country collaboration and coordination
of efforts; and
</P>
<P>
-- Promote basic and operational research to ensure that new
tools, including vaccines, are made available without delay and
existing ones are used in the most cost-effective and sustainable
manner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Advisors Criticize Bonn's Gold Revaluation, Telekom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Council of Economic Experts
has criticized government plans to revaluate Bundesbank gold
reserves and to speed up sale of the state-owned Telecom company
in efforts to qualify for the single European currency euro.
</P>
<P>
The council, which advises the German government, said in the
letter to Chancellor Helmut Kohl dated May 23 and published today
that it "regards this action as inappropriate for remedying the
undesirable developments in public finances."
</P>
<P>
Kohl and Finance Minister Theo Waigel wanted to raise the book
value of Bundesbank's 95 million fine ounces of gold to 60 percent
of the current market price from the 25 percent at present,
expecting to yield a 20 billion mark (11.6 billion US dollar)
windfall for the government.
</P>
<P>
Waigel has been battling to fill a budget gap of up to 29
billion marks (16.82 billion dollars) this year and at least 15
billion marks (8.7 billion dollars) in 1998 so that Germany can
meet the strict budget deficit and debt limits required for euro
membership and can join euro in the year of 1999 when the single
currency is due to be launched.
</P>
<P>
Admitting an accord with the Bundesbank was still pending,
Waigel also said earlier today that he would raise new revenue by
speeding up the sale of shares of the state-owned Telecom in a bid
to ease the budget pressure this year.
</P>
<P>
Germany has failed to meet the criteria for euro membership
over recent years and most analysts believe it will fail again in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Economic Experts said in its letter that the
gold revaluation plan gave the impression that Bonn was using
"creative accounting" to qualify for joining euro.
</P>
<P>
This also "casts a shadow over the independence and credibility
of the Bundesbank," said the letter, warning that it would be
difficult for the future European central bank to reject political
influence over monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
The experts also feared that the move would encourage
scepticism over euro. Opinion polls show about two-thirds of
German people are against giving up mark for the single currency.
</P>
<P>
In his reply to the letter, Waigel defended his plan, noting
that Germany was facing "extraordinary overall economic factors"
including sharply declined tax revenues. He also stressed that the
extra gold proceeds would be used to reduce the state's 833
billion mark (483.14 billion dollar) overall debt burden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bright Future for China-S. Pacific Nations Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji
arrived back in Beijing today after an official goodwill visit to
the three South Pacific countries of Australia, Western Samoa and
New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The visit shows that China enjoys good relations with the three
countries and that there is a solid foundation and bright
prospects of further developing mutually beneficial cooperation in
all fields.
</P>
<P>
This year marks the 25th anniversary of the establishment of
Sino-Australian and Sino-New Zealand diplomatic relations. It also
marks the 22nd anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic
relations between China and Western Samoa.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the Chinese government delegation was warmly
welcomed by the governments and peoples of the three countries.
</P>
<P>
Zhu held talks and reached wide-ranging understanding with
leaders of the three nations on bilateral relations, especially on
trade and economic cooperation and international issues of common
interest.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the three countries said they wanted to make joint
efforts with China to promote mutually beneficial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During their visits, the delegation also met local government
leaders, businessmen and representatives of overseas Chinese and
Chinese nationals studying or working in the three countries.
</P>
<P>
They visited factories, farms and scientific research
institutions and saw the economic achievements made by the three
countries.
</P>
<P>
The importance the three governments attaches to the
development of their relations with China and the deep affection
the peoples of the three countries hold for Chinese people made a
deep impression on the delegates.
</P>
<P>
It is safe to say that the visit has helped enhance high-level
contacts, strengthen mutual understanding, promote mutually
beneficial cooperation and the overall development of
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The Asia-Pacific region maintains a good momentum for political
stability and economic vitality. China and the three countries,
all Asian-Pacific countries, have wide-ranging common interests
and share the same or similar views on many important world issues.
</P>
<P>
Australia, New Zealand and Western Samoa have actively
participated and promoted cooperation in the Asia-Pacific region
and have been playing important roles in world and regional
affairs.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of mutual respect and equality, China and the
three countries have held friendly consultations and dialogues on
bilateral relations and regional and world issues, and have
enjoyed friendly cooperation within global and regional
organizations, including the United Nations and the Asian and
Pacific Economic Cooperation forum.
</P>
<P>
The three countries all support China in its bid to join the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Zhu and the leaders of the three countries
said that to further strengthen friendly and mutually beneficial
cooperation between their countries is not only in the fundamental
interests of their peoples, but also of great importance to
safeguarding peace and stability and promoting economic prosperity
in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the three countries said that they believe the
vigorous economic development of China will not pose any threat to
any country and a strong and prosperous China will make a greater
contribution to peace and development in the Asian Pacific region
and the world at large.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bright Future for China-S. Pacific Nations Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Leaders of the three countries also appreciated the
implementation of the policies of "one country, two systems,"
"Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong with a high degree of
autonomy" and "maintaining Hong Kong's long-term prosperity and
stability" after China resumes the exercise of sovereignty over
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese said that they believe economic and trade
cooperation between Hong Kong and the three countries will have a
much greater development in the future.
</P>
<P>
One the question of Taiwan, leaders of the three nations
reaffirmed their adherence to the one-China policy and their
commitment not to establish official ties with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side appreciated the stand the three countries have
taken on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The emphasis of the visit was on promoting bilateral economic
and trade. The Chinese side is happy to see that China has become
Australia's fifth largest and New Zealand's seventh largest
trading partner, as well as the biggest purchaser of wool from the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Australia and New Zealand have become China's two largest
investment destinations. Channar Iron Ore of Australia and a tree
farm in New Zealand, both joint ventures run with China, have made
good profits.
</P>
<P>
Economic and technological cooperation between China and
Western Samoa have also generated clear social benefits.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the Chinese delegation held broad exchanges
of view with the leaders of the three countries on expanding
bilateral trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
China, Australia and New Zealand unanimously agreed to
strengthen the Sino-Australian and Sino-New Zealand joint
committee on trade and economy.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side reached consensus with the governments of
Australia and New Zealand on enhancing cooperation in mining, iron
and steel, energy, finance, insurance, agriculture, animal
husbandry, forestry and tourism.
</P>
<P>
China and West Samoa agreed to expand economic and
technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises from China and Australia signed two documents to
jointly develop reduced iron.
</P>
<P>
All of this will undoubtedly help relations between China and
the three countries maintain long-term, stable and sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
China's economy complements those of Australia and New Zealand
and there is great potential for cooperation between China and the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Australia and New Zealand are two developed countries with rich
natural resources and strengths in certain economic fields.
</P>
<P>
China has a long-term need for many of their products, such as
iron ore, timber and wool. Meanwhile, mechanical, electronic and
textile products from China, known for their low price and good
quality, are well-regarded by the peoples of Australia, New
Zealand and Western Samoa.
</P>
<P>
China is the largest developing country in the world. Its
economic development is characterized by high growth and low
inflation and an increasing openness to the outside world. These
are favorable conditions for deepening and expanding economic and
trade cooperation with the three nations.
</P>
<P>
The great potential for bilateral cooperation will be tapped
more speedily and comprehensively as long as we grasp
opportunities and try to find new areas and ways of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government delegation extends heartfelt gratitude
to the governments and peoples of the three countries for their
careful arrangements and efforts in making the visit a success.
</P>
<P>
We believe that through common effort, the friendly, mutually
beneficial cooperative relationship between China and Australia,
New Zealand and Western Samoa will move up to a new and higher
level in the 21st century. 
</P>
