<HEADLINE> Ghana Plans 60,000-Ton Cotton Output by 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Ghana is to double its seed cotton
production to 60,000 tons by the year 2002 from the present 30,000
tons, according to a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The plan was approved last Thursday by a 30-member cotton working
group comprising government officials, producers, millers, bankers and
researchers.
</P>
<P>
"We have a long way to go but hopefully we will reach the target of
60,000 tons by 2002," said Joe Oki, managing director of Juni Agro Ltd
and a member of the working group.
</P>
<P>
Juni Agro, which takes a market share of 300 tons of lint cotton,
is Ghana's fourth largest cotton marketing company.
</P>
<P>
The west African country also has eight other companies engaged in
cotton marketing, while three major cotton firms are operating
ginneries.
</P>
<P>
Ghana does not export seed cotton. All its production is sold to
local textile companies.  
</P>
