<HEADLINE> European Union Extends Sanctions Against Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) on Tuesday
announced the extension of its limited sanctions imposed on Nigeria
for another six months, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken by EU foreign ministers at a meeting in
Brussel, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Though it confirmed "certain positive signs from the government",
the meeting decided that the human rights situation in Nigeria has not
improved much to warrant a rescission of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
EU imposed sanctions on Nigeria in the wake of the hanging of
author Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other Ogoni activists by the Nigerian
government for murdur in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions include a ban on the issuance of visas to the
Nigerian military leaders and their families, an arms embargo as
well as a freeze on sports links with any EU members.  
</P>
