<HEADLINE> New French Socialist Government Formed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
today formed his new Socialist government, which includes eight
women ministers and state secretaries and three Communist
ministers and state secretaries.
</P>
<P>
Jospin met with President Jacques Chirac twice today before
deciding on the final list of the government, composed of 14
ministers, two delegate ministers and 10 state secretaries.
</P>
<P>
The key post of justice minister and guard of the seal was
taken by a woman, former Socialist minister Elisabeth Guigou,
while that of interior minister was taken by the leader of the
Citizen's Movement party, former Defense Minister Pierre
Chevenement.
</P>
<P>
Socialists Hubert Vedrine and Alain Richard took over the key
posts of foreign minister and defense minister, while the Ministry
of Economy, Finance and Industry is headed by Dominique
Strauss-Kahn, also a Socialist.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Equipment, Transport and Housing and the
Ministry of Youth and Sports are headed by Jean-Claude Gayssot and
Marie-George Buffet, both of them from the Communists Party.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the Green Party, Dominique Voynet, takes over the
Ministry of Territory Management and Environment.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Public Service, Reform of State and
Decentralization is headed by Emile Zuccarelli from the Radical
Socialist Party.
</P>
<P>
The woman mayor of Strasbourg, Catherine Trautmann, was named
minister of culture and communication and government spokesperson.
Martine Aubry, another prominent woman in the Socialist Party,
became the minister of employment and solidarity.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of National Education, Research and Technology is
headed by Claude Guigou, the Ministry of Agriculture and Fishing
by Louis le Pensec, and the Ministry of Relations with Parliament
by Daniel Vaillant, all of them Socialists. 
</P>
