<HEADLINE> Zanzibar GDP Increases by 6.3 Percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Zanzibar gross domestic
product (GDP) grew 6.3 percent last year, as against 3.7 percent
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
This was announced in the town of Zanzibar today by Minister
of State in the President's Office Ali Juma Shamhuna at the
1997/98 development plan budget session of the House of
Representatives of Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
Shamhuna told the house that the growth in economy last year
was achieved despite the existence of many problems including the
long dry spell and "silent sanctions", probably referring to the
suspension of aid by a number of donor countries and agencies.
</P>
<P>
The minister attributed the GDP growth to the increase in
clove production as well as the contribution from other economic
sectors which led to the increase in local resources.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar last year recorded good clove yield ever in the past
few years, in which 10,105 tons were harvested.
</P>
<P>
The minister also outlined measures to boost the economy of
Zanzibar which include the setting up of a conducive environment
for investors, the improvement of telecommunications,
communications network and consolidation of the tourism sector.
</P>
