<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-04 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait, Australia Firms Sign Offset Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait and an Australian
company signed a memorandum of understanding today within the
framework of a Kuwaiti Offset Program under which the company is
obligated to invest 4.5 million U.S. dollars in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The Aerospace-Australia Company signed the agreement with the
Kuwaiti Finance Ministry after winning a contract to sell armored
vehicles Shorland S600 worth 15 million dollars to Kuwait, the
official Kuwait News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait started implementing the Offset Program in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The program stipulates that foreign companies which win
contract worth more than 1 million Kuwaiti dinars (3.3
million U.S. dollars) have to invest a sum of money equaling 30
percent of the contract value in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Offset Program mainly applies to defense contracts, and
foreign defense contractors are able to set up joint ventures
with Kuwaiti nationals in third countries.
</P>
<P>
Mazen Madoh, director of Offset Department in Kuwaiti Finance
Ministry said that up to now 18 companies from the United States,
Britain, France, Japan, Russia, Norway and Australia have been
already committed to the Offset Program with 1.5-billion-dollar
investment obligations.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's Offset Program consists of four stages, with the
signing of a contract as the first, concluding a memorandum as
the second, the approval of the idea of the project presented by
foreign companies as the third and approval of the final work
plan as the fourth.
</P>
<P>
The contract with Aerospace-Australia is on the second phase.
</P>
<P>
So far eight projects have been finally approved and carried
out in Kuwait under the program. The projects include an
aluminium factory, an academic and vocational education school,
a waterproof membranes project, a veterinary health project and
pumice rock production, official sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
