<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Sound Record Underpins Credit Rating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Credit Rating Agency
(IBCA) today assigned a long-term foreign currency rating of BBB-
(BBB minus) to all senior, unsecured debt issues of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
This investment grade rating applies to over 50 billion US
dollars of public and publicly guaranteed foreign currency debt
and will set a ceiling for IBCA rated banks and corporation in
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The IBCA also issued a long-term local currency rating of A in
recognition of Indonesia's strong fiscal position and low
inflation.
</P>
<P>
The agency said, "Indonesia has an outstanding record of
economic development: real GDP growth has averaged 7 percent annum
over the last 25 years, putting it among the High Performing Asian
Economies."
</P>
<P>
"Per capita GDP has risen over ten-fold from less than 100 US
dollars in 1970 to 1,132 US dollars in 1996, elevating the country
to lower middle income status," it added.
</P>
<P>
Steadfast adherence to sound macro-economic policy management,
complemented by structural adjustment, has been the key to
Indonesia's success, according to the IBCA.
</P>
<P>
However, the IBCA said that the country's external debts act as
major constraint on the rating.
</P>
<P>
Although the continuity of economic policy in Indonesia does
not appear to be under threat, the lack of transparency is a
growing source of uncertainty, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
