<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Peace Activists Hold Joint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian peace
activists held a joint peace march this afternoon toward the
site of the Har Homa Jewish settlement to mark the 30th
anniversary of the Israeli occupation of East Jerusalem since
1967.
</P>
<P>
At the initiative of the Israeli Peace Bloc, Gush Shalom,
Israeli peace activists set out from inside the Jewish state and
march to the site while Palestinians proceeded simultaneously
from the Palestinian protest tent camp south of the site. The two
processions met at the site to symbolically show their
solidarity.
</P>
<P>
Gush Shalom said, in a statement distributed to the press here,
that the timing of the march was chosen both because of its
proximity to the 30th anniversary of East Jerusalem's occupation
by the Israeli army, and the official Israeli "Jerusalem Day," in
which religious nationalists habitually hold provocative rallies
in East Jerusalem to mark the so-called "unification" of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"It is the opinion of Gush Shalom, as of other Israeli peace
movements, that this 'unification' is nothing but a wafer-thin
myth, an euphemism for an oppressive military occupation rule
over the 180,000 Palestinian inhabitants," it added.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that the Israeli occupation rule is
manifested in many forms.
</P>
<P>
Israel has confiscated Palestinian lands widely and
constructed on the soil neighborhoods for the Jews only.
</P>
<P>
The prohibition on Arab construction in East Jerusalem still
takes effect despite numerous statements on the issue published
by the Netanyahu government in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Arab houses are often demolished by the Israeli authorities.
</P>
<P>
Extreme-right settlers penetrate into Arab neighborhoods,
using various legal tricks and government-financed "sales," and
have led to what the statement called the creation of armed
settler enclaves.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Interior Ministry have expelled outright thousands
of Palestinian Jerusalemites, whose right of residence is denied
by the ministry on various pretexts.
</P>
<P>
"All of these measures, taken together, amount to nothing
less than a policy of ethnic cleansing, which can only lead to a
total confrontation between the two peoples, in Jerusalem and
elsewhere," declared Gush Shalom in the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
