<HEADLINE> Environment Conservation Urged in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Vice-President
Omar Ali Juma today stressed that all development activities to
be undertaken should consider environment conservation.
</P>
<P>
In his message to mark the World Environment Day today, Juma
said history shows that development activities which were carried
out without considering their impacts to the environment are
endangering the lives of living things including the people.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will take all possible measures to
avert environmental problems to be caused by the social and
economic development undertakings.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president said the steps to be taken includes the
strengthening of the Environmental Impact Assessment Unit which
is under his office as well as investing more on environmental
conservation initiatives.
</P>
<P>
He, however, said people's participation in protecting the
environment is very essential in making the government efforts a
success.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to take this opportunity to ask every individual
to participate fully in environmental issues. Let us plant trees.
Let us not pollute water sources. Let us stop invading government
conservation areas, illegal fishing and any other activities that
endanger our environment," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president said the World Environment Day this year is
being marked under the theme "for life for earth", with an aim to
remind the people on the importance of conserving the
environment.
</P>
<P>
He said environmental degradation is a result of improper land
use, the use of chemicals, illegal fishing, deforestation and
many other environmental unfriendly activities. 
</P>
