<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to Ask FEC to Ban "Soft Money" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The White House confirmed U.S.
President Bill Clinton plans to appeal directly to the Federal
Election Commission to outlaw the limitless contributions to
political parties known as "soft money."
</P>
<P>
White House press secretary Mike McCurry said Clinton decided
to pursue action through the FEC after deciding there is now
virtually no chance Congress will meet the challenge in his State
of the Union speech for enacting campaign finance reform
legislation on its own before July 4.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said Clinton "would love for it to (meet the July 4
deadline), but as a practical matter that won't happen."
</P>
<P>
Federal law limits political contributions by groups and
individuals to candidates, but donors found a major loophole known
as "soft money" by making their contributions through their
political parties.
</P>
<P>
The so-called "soft money" given to parties is limited to
"party-building" purposes, but Democrats and Republicans have
stretched the limits of that definition to include virtually a
full array of activities benefiting individual candidates.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said Clinton would base his FEC appeal on the grounds
that FEC definitions following the 1974 campaign finance reforms
"opened the loophole for soft money that then expanded
significantly throughout the '70s and '80s, and so it's within the
power of the commission to close the loophole." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
