<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Hotel Industry Shake-Up Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The European hotel industry will be
shaken up by mergers and joint ventures in the next few years as
large international hotel chains vie to increase their presence,
said a report released here today.
</P>
<P>
Occupancy levels at European hotels rose by 2 percent last year
to 72.2 percent, according to the Hotel Industry Benchmark Survey
1997.
</P>
<P>
London enjoyed the highest average occupancy levels of 84.3
percent. Hotels in Rome, with marginally lower occupancy rates,
were the most expensive.
</P>
<P>
Average revenue per room in Rome rose by 22 percent to 185.13
Deutsche marks (some 107 US dollars), due to a rise in tourism, a
lack of new hotels and a strengthening of the lira against the
mark.
</P>
<P>
Large international hotel chains, such as Marriott, Hilton
Hotel Corporation and Inter-Continental, will target regional and
large national players while continuing to acquire small European
groups.
</P>
<P>
Consolidation is also likely in the mid-market sector as
smaller groups merge or collaborate in join ventures, in order to
expand nationally and reduce overheads, said Arthur Andersen, the
accountancy firm, which surveyed 1,000 hotels of three-star
standard and above.
</P>
<P>
Europe received half the world's international tourism
expenditure last year but the health of its hotel industry varied
widely between countries.
</P>
<P>
Difficult economic conditions continued to affect hotels in
France and Germany. Occupancy levels in Paris were static while
those in Berlin and Frankfurt fell back last year compared to
1995, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
