today their willingness to ensure the continuity of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
This came after Saudi Foreign Minister Prince Saud met with
King Hussein, Crown Prince Hassan and Prime Minister Abdul Salam
Majali during his two-day visit which ended today.
</P>
<P>
The visit was against the backdrop that the U.S. and Egypt
failed to reactivate the deadlocked Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi minister voiced appreciation over the "advanced
level" of cooperative relations between Amman and Riyadh and
expressed gratitude for Saudi support to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
He said that both sides shared identical views that peace is an
international strategy and that it was Israel that hindered the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed means to promote bilateral ties,
and regional and international issues of mutual concern,
particularly inter-Arab ties.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Jordan and Saudi Arabia suffered setbacks
during the Gulf Crisis as Jordan sided with Iraq. About 3 million
Jordanians working in Saudi Arabia were then driven out of the
country.
</P>
<P>
After the crisis, Jordan distanced itself from Iraq in order to
end international isolation. Its ties with Saudi Arabia also began
to pick up.
</P>
<P>
Now Saudi Arabia is the kingdom's second largest Arab trade
partner after Iraq. In 1996, Jordan exported some 184 million
U.S. dollars worth of goods to Saudi Arabia, up from about 99
million in 1995. 
</P>
