<HEADLINE> Botswana to Offer New Proposal on Ivory Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Botswana will present a new
plan to a Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species
meeting in Zimbabwe next week, a top Botswanan official said
today.
</P>
<P>
The new proposal is for limited and controlled trade in
stockpiled ivory with one buyer, Botswana's Commerce and Industry
Minister George Kgoroba told a press conference in Gaborone.
</P>
<P>
"Funds from the trade will be used to establish wildlife
management programs that will eventually include culling,"
Kgoroba said.
</P>
<P>
Botswana reportedly wants to sell 25 tons of stockpiled ivory.
It says that a Japanese buyer has been identified and has agreed
not to re-export the ivory or products made from it.
</P>
<P>
According to Botswana wildlife officials, the country's
elephant population totaled 79,000 in 1995, with an annual
growth of five percent.
</P>
<P>
Botswana's Deputy Director of Wildlife Joseph Matlhare said
that his country wants only to reduce its stockpile of ivory.
"There will be no killing to build up the stockpile," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
For now, in addition to Botswana, Zimbabwe and Namibia also
seek a partial lifting of the 1989 ban on ivory trade. 
</P>
