<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses US of Balking Supply for Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iraqi official here today
accused the United States of blocking the supplies needed for the
country's education.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Minister of Education Abdul Jabbar Toufiq told reporters
that up till now, Iraq has not received anything that is needed
for education in accordance with the "oil-for-food" deal signed
by Iraq and the United Nations last year.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. Sanctions Committee has not approved any contracts
relating to the educational sector," although five months have
passed since such contracts in this regard were handed over to
the committee, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He accused the U.S. representative on the committee of
opposing the ratification of the contracts.
</P>
<P>
However, Iraq will "continue the education process even if
(Iraqi) students have to sit on the ground and use the feather
to write on date-palm leaves," he said.
</P>
<P>
The "oil-for-food" deal allowed Iraq to sell 2 billion
U.S. dollars worth of oil over six months to pay for food,
medicine and other basic commodities badly needed in the country
to alleviate the sufferings of the Iraqis following the seven-year
U.N. sanctions since Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
About 12 million dollars from the oil revenues was earmarked
for Iraq's educational sector. The education minister said, "This
is a very small amount" compared with 1.6 billion dollars before
the sanctions started.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the official Iraqi news agency quoted an
unnamed spokesman of the Ministry of Information and Culture as
saying that the U.S. has so far suspended 200 contracts to
supply Iraq with humanitarian commodities.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council approved on the same day the
extension of the "oil-for-food' deal, which will expire on June
7, for another six months. 
</P>
