<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Further Development of Sino-Italian Ties Stressed (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said here
today that the further development of Sino-Italian relations is
helpful for the establishment of a world pattern featuring
multi-polarization and a just and rational new international order
for politics and economy.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese leader made the remark during his talks here today
with Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China considers the
growth of relations between China and Italy as an important part
of the overall progress of Sino-European ties, and to reinforce
bilateral ties conforms to the interests of the two countries and
the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, the two prime ministers exchanged views on
bilateral relations and issues of common concern with consensus
reached on many issues.
</P>
<P>
Li recalled his two visits to Italy as prime minister and his
friendly talks with Prodi last year when he attended the World
Food Summit held in Rome, saying that the talks had deepened
mutual understanding and enhanced friendship.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that since Prodi is accompanied by many
Italian enterpreneurs this time, his visit will be of great
significance to the further advancement of bilateral economic and
trade ties as well as co-operation in other sectors.
</P>
<P>
China and Italy, both with ancient civilization,
have a long history of friendly contacts, the Chinese premier
said, noting bilateral relations have grown rapidly and achieved
many positive results since the establishment of diplomatic ties
in 1970 and especially over the recent years.
</P>
<P>
China attaches great importance to the development of a
long-term and stable friendship and relations of co-operation with
Italy, and is willing to expand co-operation in politics, economy,
trade, culture, technology and other fields, he said.
</P>
<P>
Prodi's present visit demonstrated the Italian government's
willingness to actively promote bilateral ties, Li noted,
expressing the belief that through concerted efforts of both
sides, Sino-Italian friendship and co-operation will be expanded
on the basis of mutual respect, seeking common ground while
reserving differences, and equality and mutual benefit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Further Development of China-Italian Ties Stressed (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li pointed out that in recent years, bilateral economic and
trade relations have been reinforced, contacts between the
business circles of the two countries increased, and Italian
investment in China kept rising. Italy has joined
the 100-seat aircraft production program of China, Li noted,
describing this as a "new content" in bilateral co-operation.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said that in recent years, Italy and China have
expand their co-operation in various spheres, and bilateral ties
have kept growing. He said that later this year, Italy will
organize a large-scale fair in China.
</P>
<P>
Italy, as China's second largest trade partner in Europe, will
try to keep this position while seeking new co-operation ways in
a bid to ensure a comprehensive and in-depth development of such
relations.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Italy and China hold the same or similar
views on many international issues and China is playing an
important role in world affairs. He expressed the hope Italy and
China will have a better co-operation in the United Nation and
other international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Italy supports China to join the World Trade Organization,
Prodi reiterated.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong's return to China is worth celebrating,
and the policy of "one country, two systems" is a creation full of
wisdom.
</P>
<P>
Li said that Hong Kong's return is in sight, and China is
confident about the development prospect after its return,
stressing the legitimate rights and interests of Italian business
people or people of other circles in Hong Kong will be protected.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, the two prime ministers also attended a
signing ceremony of four documents including an exchange of notes
on the maintenance of Italian consulate general in the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region after July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talks, Li presided over a welcoming ceremony in
honor of Prodi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
