<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq to Sign More Deals With Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi delegate to the Arab League
Nabil Negm said here today that Baghdad will sign new accords with
Egyptian government and firms after the renewal of oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Negm said that Iraq and Egypt have taken long strides in recent
months towards promoting bilateral economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Meetings have been held between Iraqi and Egyptian trade
ministers and among officials of their chambers of commerce and
industries to achieve the purpose, added the delegate.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council decided Wednesday to
extend, for another six months, the agreement with Iraq, which
allows the embargo-stricken country to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars
worth of oil to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian
commodities.
</P>
<P>
Another batch of Egyptian pharmaceuticals worth 1.53 million
dollars will be shipped to Iraq in a few days under the new
contracts approved this month by the Sanction Committee under the
U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official accused the United States and Britain of
interfering in the implementation of the deal which is designed to
ease the sufferings of the Iraqi people under seven years of
international embargo.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite the fact that his country has signed over
700 agreements on importing food and medicines since the deal came
into effect, less than 37 percent of them have been approved and
implemented mainly because of the U.S. stance.
</P>
<P>
"They are still working to impede giving green light to
implement accords concluded by Iraq with several countries in
accordance with the deal," said the Iraqi delegate to the Arab
League.
</P>
<P>
"The American attitude was the main reason behind the delay in
distributing food quotas on the Iraqi people and it has thwarted
the objectives of the memo of understanding concluded between Iraq
and the UN," he added.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has previously complained that very little medicine, and
only 700,000 tons of the 2.4 million tons of food expected as a
result of the deal, have arrived since oil began to flow in
December.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has signed several agreements on exporting medicines to
Iraq but apparently failed to reach the targeted 100 million
dollars of exports in the first six months since the deal took
effect.
</P>
<P>
The deal is an exemption from the U.N. sanctions imposed after
Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait. U.N. diplomats have said they will
not consider lifting the sanctions until they are satisfied that
Iraq has fully cooperated with U.N. arms inspectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
