<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Urges Party to Fight Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad today called on the ruling United Malays National
Organization (UMNO) and government members to steadfastly fight
corruption.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir, who is now abroad on a two-month long vacation, made
the call during a 15-minute video tele-conferencing connecting
him in London with Acting prime minister Anwar Ibrahim at the UMNO
headquarters here, the Malaysian national news agency Bernama
reported.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir, who is UMNO president, said fighting graft required
determined efforts to prevent erosion of UMNO and the government's
credibility.
</P>
<P>
"Graft is unhealthy for the party and the government," he said,
adding "Our friends may be involved. But if we don't take action
they may think we'll defend whatever they do since we (the
government) have the powers."
</P>
<P>
According to Bernama, also present at the UMNO headquarters
were party secretary-general Sabbaruddin Chik, vice-presidents
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi and Najib Tun Razak, UMNO Youth Chief Ahmad
Zahid Hamidi, UMNO Women Wing leader Zaharah Sulaiman and party
information chief Yusof Nor.
</P>
<P>
The video tele-conferencing with Mahathir took place after
Anwar chaired a three-hour-long UMNO Supreme Council meeting at
the party headquarters, which had strongly resolved to deal with
corruption, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the fight against graft, which got full backing
from the Cabinet, should also get solid support from all UMNO
members.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir was informed by Anwar that the Supreme Council wholly
supported measures to maintain a clean image of the party and the
government and deal with corruption.
</P>
<P>
The council also discussed declaration of assets and incomes by
government officers, elected representatives, executive
councilors, chief ministers, deputy ministers and cabinet members.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, the council was also unanimous in relaying
a clear message to the party and government machineries on
anti-corruption measures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
