<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developed Nations Rebuked for Linking Trade to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries like Indonesia
should be wary of developed countries which try to pressure them
by linking trade to environmental issues, a business official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
"Developed nations often press developing countries to conserve
the environment while they leave their own environment in a state
of neglect," said Dewi Motik Pramono, chairperson for
environmental affairs of the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and
Industry.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a panel discussion on Indonesia's Agenda 21, she
said care should be taken to assess the pressure given by
developed countries to prevent them from making developing
countries merely their suppliers (of energy and natural sources).
</P>
<P>
"We are not against developed nations because they are our
business partners, but we should be rational in doing business.
(We should not) pursue profit at the expense of our interests,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Koesnadi Hardjasoemantri, former rector of the
Yogyakarta-based Gajah Mada University, said the application of
Agenda 21, adopted at the Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro in June
1992, has divided the world into two camps -- developed countries
and developing ones -- which have become suspicious of each other.
</P>
<P>
"On one hand, developed nations are often accused of
excessively exploiting the natural resources of developing
countries while on the other hand, developing countries are very
dependent on the technology of developed countries. This is one of
the factors that impede the global application of Agenda 21," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's Agenda 21 is a follow-up to the global Agenda 21
adopted at the Earth Summit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
