<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Awards Granted to Winners of International Cooperation Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- An awards ceremony was held today
in Beijing's Diaoyutai State Guest House to honor the
Chinese-American physicist Samuel C.C. Ting and the Russian
aerodynamics expert G.S. Bisigensi, the winners of the 1996 China
International Science and Technology Cooperation Prize.
</P>
<P>
Song Jian, a state councillor and the minister in charge of the
State Science and Technology Commission, granted each man a medal
and a certificate, honoring them for their outstanding
contributions to China's science and technology.
</P>
<P>
The 61-year-old Ting is the 1976 winner of the Nobel Prize for
physics and has made major contributions to China's high-energy
physics and Sino-foreign exchanges. Since 1978, he has helped more
than 100 Chinese physicists and post-graduates in labs that he
headed.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Chinese scientists participated in the ALPHA Magnetic
Spectrometer (AMS) project, the first man-made magnet to be sent
into space for experiments.
</P>
<P>
He became a foreign academician of the Chinese Academy of
Sciences, China's top research organ.
</P>
<P>
Bisigensi, 81, is a well-known Russian aerodynamics expert who
gave China extensive assistance in designing supersonic aircraft,
and helped train China's first group of aircraft designers 30
years ago.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990s, he started organizing Russian experts begin a
research program with Chinese colleagues to design the next
generation of aircraft.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Speaks on US-German Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said that
Germany and the United States should not let their differences over
policies toward countries like Iran overshadow their cooperative
relationship, a German newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Germany is an essential partner for the United States in
tackling the most important regional and global issues, Clinton
said in an exclusive interview with the German mass circulation
tabloid Bild.
</P>
<P>
He also praised Germany's role in securing peace and prosperity
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
As for the U.S.'s role in Europe, the president said, "the
Unites States has been a European power since the 1940s and will
remain such a power."
</P>
<P>
Clinton also dismissed reports that U.S.-German ties have
cooled recently.
</P>
<P>
"We have been hearing these rumors for 20 years or more. They
were unfounded then as they are now."
</P>
<P>
Germany had irked Washington by calling for a dialogue with
Iran, but relations between Bonn and Tehran took a downturn in
April after a German court ruled that Iran was behind the
assassination of Iranian Kurds in Berlin in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The publication of the interview coincided with German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's stay in Washington, where Clinton is to
host celebrations commemorating the 50th anniversary of the
Marshall Plan on Thursday. The plan helped the reconstruction of
post-war Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
