<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania to Give Preferential Treatment to Foreign Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investors are to be given
preferential treatment by the Romanian government following an
emergency decree issued today amending its Foreign Capital Act.
</P>
<P>
The series of measures designed to make Romania an attractive
place for foreign investment include exemptions from income tax
and import tariffs for businesses investing more than 300,000
U.S. dollars and the ability to remit foreign currency earnings
abroad.
</P>
<P>
The preferential treatment will be based on the volume of
investment, re-investment of a venture's annual profit, use of
Romania's natural resources, infrastructure construction and new
jobs created.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors who export more than half of their production
and invest in infrastructure, tourism, environmental protection
or underdeveloped areas will also get preferential treatment, the
decree said.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to jump start the country's stock market,
foreigners buying stocks and shares will also be given
preferential treatment.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the Romanian parliament renewed the Foreign
Capital Act which was passed in 1991, permitting foreign
businessmen to buy land to be used in infrastructure construction.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Romania has seen an sharp increase in
foreign investment since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Total foreign investment in Romania reached 2.486 billion
dollars by the end of May. Holland is the biggest investor, with
264 million dollars, South Korea the second with 235 million
dollars and Germany the third with 224 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
