<HEADLINE> OIC Plans to Review Manila-MNLF Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC) has proposed to review the implementation of a
landmark peace agreement signed last September between Manila and
a former major Muslim rebel group in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Department of Foreign Affairs confirmed today
that the OIC had extended its invitation to the Philippine
government and the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) for a
meeting in Libya soon.
</P>
<P>
Under the mediation of the OIC, the MNLF and the Philippine
forged the Mindanao Peace Accord last September, ending 27-year
armed conflicts between the MNLF rebels and the government forces
in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The invitation was conveyed through the OIC Committee of Six,
chaired by Indonesia, which supervised the Manila-MNLF peace talks
and served as observers during its protracted negotiations,
sources at the department said.
</P>
<P>
The initiative to review the Mindanao Peace Accord stems from
the reported defection of many MNLF fighters to another rebel
group, the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) in the southern
Philippines, since the signing of the agreement, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
They said the OIC wants to review the agreement to help ensure
peace in Mindanao by making sure all the provisions provided in
the agreement are substantially complied with.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
