<HEADLINE> Taliban Accept Opposition's Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Islamic Taliban
militia have agreed to all the three proposals made by General
Abdul Malik aimed at resolving the on-going crisis gripping the
war-ravaged Afghanistan, a Pakistani Foreign Ministry official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The Taliban Shoora in Kandahar and their leader Mulla Muhammad
Omar have okayed these proposals," Pakistani Additional Secretary
for Afghanistan Iftikhar Murshid told a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
According to Murshid, Malik had assured the Taliban of his
cooperation in establishing an Islamic state and proposed to allow
the northern parties to exclusively control northern Afghanistan
and not to disarm these groups.
</P>
<P>
Murshid said the proposals were jotted down on May 19, some
eight days before clashes erupted between Malik's forces and
Taliban fighters in Mazar-e-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
He said the Taliban leadership expressed their willingness to
accept the proposals on May 31 and "the response from General
Malik is expected anytime."
</P>
<P>
Murshid quoted Malik as telling Pakistan's Consel General Ayaz
Wazir in Mazar-e-Sharif that "he is willing to extend all-out
cooperation to the Taliban."
</P>
<P>
Malik, whose defection on May 19 triggered the downfall of
northern warlord Rashid Dostum, turned his back on the Taliban
only four days after his forces and the Taliban fighters took
control of Dostum's stronghold Mazar-e-Sharif on May 24.  
</P>
