<HEADLINE> Waste Water Treatment Project In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Work on the second phase of a
waste water treatment project began today in Shanghai, which will
handle 1.7 million tons of industrial and everyday life waste
water daily when it is completed.
</P>
<P>
The first phase was completed in 1990, and since then water
quality in the Suzhou River has improved. A 35-km conduit in the
northern part of Shanghai handles 1.2 million tons of waste water
daily, for a 70-sq-km area.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the waste water treatment project will
cost five billion yuan including 250 million US dollars in loans
from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The project will involve the laying of 51.8-km-long conduit from
Shanghai's main water source - the middle reaches of the Huangpu
River. It will serve 3.56 million people in a 271-sq-km
area in the southern part of the city. It is scheduled for
completion in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
