<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet's Environmental Report For 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, Jane 5 (Xinhua) -- Tibet had no acid rain or any
pollution accidents in 1996, according to a report on
environmental conditions for 1996 released here today.
</P>
<P>
The report, released by the Tibet Autonomous Regional
government, showed that water quality in the main rivers of the
region is good, and in line with state environmental quality
standards.
</P>
<P>
Underground water quality was also generally good, the report
said, and most of the more than 1,500 lakes with a total water
surface of 24,000 sq km maintain their primary conditions and good
water quality.
</P>
<P>
Air quality in 1996 was the same as the previous year, and
accords with state standard for grade-II air quality.
</P>
<P>
However, it reported, noise pollution in Lhasa, the region's
capital, got worse in 1996 because of the increasing number of
automobiles.
</P>
<P>
The rural environment in Tibet was good on the whole, and the
region was free from pesticide pollution. In order to keep the
"roof of the world" clean, the report said, a great deal of effort
is needed to prevent pollution and improve the ecology. This
includes afforestation and the increased use of solar energy.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the environmental protection achievements
in Tibet mostly to the environment-related legal work and
increasing environmental protection awareness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0105 </DOCNO>
