<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Tell the World the Truth About HK (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Everyday Kevin Sinclair spends
long hours working at his computer, and every week he gets his
articles printed in local English newspapers and overseas
publications.
</P>
<P>
"What I've been doing is to try to tell the world the truth
about Hong Kong," said Sinclair in an exclusive interview with
Xinhua in his home office in the Hong Kong Polytechnic Staff
Quarters in Fo Tan.
</P>
<P>
The strongly-built Sinclair is an Occidental who has lived in
Hong Kong for over 30 years and has always considered himself
part of Hong Kong despite the difference of his hair and eye
colors from local Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair has difficulty in talking due to a throat operation
many years ago, but that does not hinder him from opening a column
in South China Morning Post which he called "conversations".
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes it's difficult to tell the truth," he said. "Because
many people overseas are so ignorant. They think that Hong Kong is
going to die in July -- which is rubbish. We're going to get
better, with a better life for everyone."
</P>
<P>
Sinclair said he likes talking and is good at it although he
has to exert himself, often with gestures, to make himself clear.
</P>
<P>
Having witnessed the exciting changes of Hong Kong in the past
few decades, Sinclair believes he is qualified to tell the story
of Hong Kong, not some foreign reporters who come here "with
stupid ideas to write stupid things".
</P>
<P>
"Reporters should just report what they see and what is
happening here, instead of choosing the bad or the good," he said.
"Whenever Chinese officials come to Hong Kong, it's always the
same 20 people demonstrating, and some reporters only concentrate
on the handful of demonstrators while ignoring the six million who
are working. This is unfair for Hong Kong people." His cheeks
turned red as he became excited.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair cherishes profound feelings for Hong Kong and the
Chinese mainland. He knows well the history and culture of China,
which are reflected in his social, political and food columns and
other works. And all these originated from a book he read when he
was Young.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair was born on a farm in New Zealand in 1942. At 14, he
read "Red Star Over China" written by Edgar Snow, which aroused
his interest in China.
</P>
<P>
He left school at the age of 16 and worked for different
newspapers from messenger boy to reporter, and finally came to
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"I came by ship, because my parents were very poor and couldn't
afford to buy a plane ticket," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said at that time Hong Kong was as poor as he was. The hills
were covered in squatter huts, people had nothing but pride and
hope. Nevertheless, he loved this piece of land the moment he
stepped on it.
</P>
<P>
"Look at Hong Kong today. It is fantastic what has been
achieved," he said.
</P>
<P>
Now Hong Kong people are generally rich and confident, and they
play a big role in international financial and business councils.
And this will surely continue considering their marvelous
resilience to adapt to different circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair has a hobby of long-distance cycling, usually three
times a week. And he likes to stop in villages to talk to the
people.
</P>
<P>
"Many of my best friends are Hakka farmers," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Hopes to Get 5 Billion U.S. Dollars From CGI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia hopes that the
Consultative Group for Indonesia (CGI), which convenes in the
middle of this month in Tokyo, Japan, would provide 5 billion U.S.
dollars in loans for it, a senior official said here today.
</P>
<P>
State Minister for National Development Planning Ginandjar
Kartasasmita told reporters after meeting with President Soeharto
that Indonesia must be prepared for a possible decline in CGI aid.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia secured 5.26 billion U.S. dollars in loans from the
CGI, which is composed of 18 countries and 11 international
agencies, at the conclusion of its meeting in Paris on June 19-20
last year.
</P>
<P>
The loans consisted of 2.563 billion U.S. dollars from the 18
CGI countries and 2.696 billion U.S. dollars from the
international agencies.
</P>
<P>
If Indonesia expects a 5 billion U.S. dollars loan, it must
heed the ceiling on loans each CGI country and international body
will give to Indonesia, said Ginandjar, who will leave for Japan
on June 8 to hold preparatory talks with Japanese officials.
</P>
<P>
On the possibility the CGI will cut its assistance, the
minister said a reduction in CGI loans is possible as Indonesia
has been categorized as a middle-income country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Tell the World the Truth About HK (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sinclair is also proud of his own achievements in Hong Kong: "I
have got one wife, two children and written 13 books."
</P>
<P>
He showed some of his works to the reporter, most of which are
about Hong Kong and China, covering such areas as the environment,
Hong Kong police, Chinese cooking, the Yellow River and Chinese
national minorities.
</P>
<P>
His columns and books have made him a name both in Hong Kong
and the mainland, and he attributed that to hardworking.
</P>
<P>
"Having cancer and not being able to talk properly were a great
advantage. That made me tougher. It made me harder," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong is my home. I have lived here more than half my
life. I met my wife here, we had our two children here and we own
our home here -- we are Hong Kongers."
</P>
<P>
Sinclair's wife, Kit Allred, teaches medicine and helps
handicapped people at the Hong Kong Polytechnic University. She
also has courses in universities in Hebei, Anhui and Guangdong
provinces on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair said his wife is just like him -- she is also
committed to China and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
His 21-year-old son, David, is studying in California, while
his 19-year-old daughter Kiri is studying in Brisbane. "She hopes
to go to Beijing University next year," he said.
</P>
<P>
While dwelling on Hong Kong's changes for the better, Sinclair
is also worried about some changes which he believes are very bad,
especially the deterioration of the environment.
</P>
<P>
"The worst thing about Hong Kong is pollution. Sometimes the
air is so dirty that I'm scared to go for a bike ride," he said.
"I'm very glad that Tung Chee Hwa is concerned about the
environment."
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the handover at midnight on June 30, he said there
is nothing to be worried about. On the handover day he will stay
at home, working as usual.
</P>
<P>
Sinclair has been visiting mainland provinces quite regularly
and has an intimate knowledge of China.
</P>
<P>
"I've interviewed many Chinese leaders, and I think the Chinese
government will do anything to make Hong Kong successful," he
said, showing this reporter around his roomy house to see pictures
taken with his Chinese friends, Chinese paintings and collections.
</P>
<P>
He said that in China's history never have so many Chinese been
so wealthy, so healthy, so well-educated and had such a measure of
real freedom since Deng Xiaoping's policies threw open the doors
of China to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
"I believe sincerely that the government, bureaucracy, party
and army are united in promoting Hong Kong's welfare -- not out of
any altruistic reasons but because a prosperous and safe Hong Kong
means a richer and more powerful China," he said.
</P>
<P>
He admits that with the handover to China, there will be some
changes, people will lose some of the advantages of the western
way of life. "But we have to be realists. We are going to be part
of China and if we want to remain in Hong Kong, we had better be
prepared to play by Chinese rules. If you don't like it, go. I
will stay."
</P>
<P>
He said many of his western friends in Hong Kong hold similar
views. They will stay in Hong Kong as long as they are happy with
their jobs, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
