<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most S. Africans Backs Overseas Peacekeeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The majority of the South
African people supported the participation of the national armed
forces in peacekeeping operations, according to a survey released
here today.
</P>
<P>
Nearly two-thirds of (62 percent) of respondents expressed
that they were in favour of South African troops being sent
outsdie the country for peacekeeping operations, the survey by
the Human Sciences Research Council and the Institute for Securty
Studies (ISS) said.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted among 4,400 respondents in urban and
rural areas throughout South Africa, might reflect the view that
the security of South Africa could not be pursued in isolation
from that of its neighbors, ISS Executive Director Jaki Cilliers
said.
</P>
<P>
It indicated South Africans support the concept of common, or
collaborative security in the Southern African region, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the cost and pitfalls of the regional peacekeeping,
there is immense pressure on South Africa to become a major
contributor to the evolution of sub-regional capacity for peace
operations, Cilliers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
