<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Inflation Rate Down in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The year-on-year inflation rate in
the Philippines slowed down to 4.2 percent in May this year from
4.6 percent in April as prices of food, beverages and tobacco
continued to decline in the month, the National Statistics Office
said today.
</P>
<P>
"On a month-on-month basis, the inflation rate was zero in May
as the index marginally moved down from its previous month's
level," the office said in a report released here today.
</P>
<P>
On a year-on-year basis, it said, the inflation rate in the
food, beverages and tobacco went down 0.6 percent in May while
rates for fuel, light and water declined 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The inflation for food alone was down 1 percent last month from
1.5 percent in April, it said.
</P>
<P>
But the rate for services went up 0.2 percent, it added.
</P>
<P>
The country's average inflation rate in the first four months
of this year is 4.7 percent and the government is targeting a 6 to
6.5 percent annual rate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
