<HEADLINE> Profit-Takers Move in as Australian Shares Sink </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Profit-takers knocked shares down
across the board on the Australian share market today, with the
soft base metal and gold prices counteracting modest gains in the
banking sector.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index slipped 11.7 points to close at
2604.2.
</P>
<P>
"The market just seems to be idling ahead of the long weekend
and with new jobs data out in the U.S. tomorrow night," a
Sydney-based trader said.
"There was a fair bit of profit-taking which didn't help
momentum."
</P>
<P>
Traders said the market hovered for much of the day before a
late burst of selling towards the close, with many investors
likely to be away tomorrow for an extended Queen's Birthday long
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Many were also positioning ahead of the release of U.S. May
jobs data tomorrow night.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index fell 10.9 points to 1480.3 while the
all industrials index lost 13.6 points to 4067.2.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was also down, losing 16.6 points to 1549.4 in
the wake of Wednesday's 2.10 U.S. dollar fall in the gold price.
</P>
<P>
Gold bullion closed in Sydney at 341.35 U.S. dollars an ounce
from 343.70 U.S. dollars last.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 359.08 million shares worth 853.56
million Australian dollars (648.70 million U.S. dollars), with
falls outnumbering rises 618 to 452.
</P>
<P>
Westpac Banking Corp. was one of the heaviest traded stocks
amid rumors that its 1.4 billion Australian dollar (1.06 billion
U.S. dollar) bid for Bank of Melbourne Ltd. was unlikely to be
approved by the ACCC.
</P>
<P>
Westpac was also the center of takeover speculation, with
suggestions that a major offshore institution has approached the
Foreign Investment Review Board with regard to a takeover.
</P>
<P>
More than 7.49 million Westpac shares were traded worth 53.19
million Australian dollars (40.42 million U.S. dollars). Westpac
shares closed 25 cents higher at 7.20 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Melbourne shares fell to their lowest level in eight
weeks, losing 39 cents to close at 8.95 Australian dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
