<HEADLINE> S. Korean President's Son Indicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 5 (Xinhua) -- South Korean prosecutors today
indicted Kim Hyun-chul, the second son of President Kim Young-sam,
on bribery and tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
The junior Kim's close aide Kim Ki-sup, former deputy director
of the National Security Planning, was also indicted on graft
charges.
</P>
<P>
The trial for the president's son and his five aides is
expected to open early next month, according to court officials.
</P>
<P>
The 38-year-old junior Kim was arrested on May 17 on charges of
taking 3.6 million U.S. dollars in return for favors from two
business firms.
</P>
<P>
"We have concluded a supplementary probe into the junior Kim's
influence-peddling and scale, sources and expenditures of his
slush fund," said the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
The probe concluded that the president's son is suspected of
having received a total of 7.4 million U.S. dollars from six
businessmen, 3.6 million dollars in return for favors and 3.8
million under the name of "operational funds."
</P>
<P>
For the "operation fund", if not bribe, Kim will have to pay
1.46 million U.S. dollars in penalties on tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
The investigation also revealed that Kim had managed a slush
fund worth more than 16.9 million dollars, some of which were from
the businessmen.
</P>
<P>
But the prosecutors refused to disclose the details of the
sources, management and the expenditure of the slush fund, in a
bid to avoid what they called "possible negative political impact."
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties and the public charged that the prosecutors
failed to find out the truth on Kim's alleged connection with the
collapsed Hanbo Group, his meddling in state affairs such as
personnel appointment and other profitable affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
