<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF's Lending Arm to Fund Kenya's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC), the International Monetary Fund's lending arm
to the private sector, is to fund Kenya's micro-enterprise bank
with one million U.S. Dollars of equity investment.
</P>
<P>
A just-signed financing agreement will facilitate the
transforming of Kenya Rural Enterprise Program (K-Rep) into a
commercial, micro-enterprise bank to be known as K-Rep Bank, the
Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
This is IFC's first direct investment in a
micro-enterprise financial institution.
</P>
<P>
The new bank will continue to provide lending and savings
services to Kenyan micro-entrepreneurs who do not have access to
formal financial institutions due to lack of collateral and high
transaction costs.
</P>
<P>
It will lend to either individual clients or groups, whereby
credit is extended to members of a group who are jointly held
accountable for repayment.
</P>
<P>
The K-Rep was initially established to provide training,
technical assistance and financial credit to micro-entrepreneurs.
Now it has the largest micro-enterprise finance operation in
Africa with a client base of over 15,000.
</P>
<P>
Its average loan size is about 300 Dollars and has achieved an
average repayment rate of about 95 percent over the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
"We expect K-Rep Bank to help extend IFC's reach to the many
micro and small-scale businesses throughout Kenya," said Tei
Mante, an IFC director.
</P>
<P>
The other major shareholders of K-Rep Bank will be South Shore
Bank of Chicago, the African Development Bank, Triodios (a Dutch
non-governmental group) and the Netherlands Development
Organization.
</P>
<P>
The IFC has also signed an agreement with Kenya's Credit
Finance Corporation Limited bank (CFC) for a loan option facility
of 10 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The hedge facility, a new product introduced by IFC, will
allow CFC Bank the right but not the obligation, to draw down
short and medium-term loans from IFC.
</P>
<P>
The CFC was set up in 1955 as the first independent
asset-based financing company in the eastern African country and
converted into a commercial bank in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
