<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar today
slipped against the U.S. dollar, the Japanese yen and the
Deutsche mark as the market awaited vital job data to be released
in the United States on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
The market, also still cautious about the prospects of another
easing in the domestic official interest rates, was met with
silence from the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) this morning, for
the second day since its monthly board meeting.
</P>
<P>
Speculation that another cut is imminent remains and the market
will be listening for news resulting from RBA Governor Ian
Macfarlane's speech overnight at Westpac's economic conference in
London.
</P>
<P>
On May 23, the RBA took the financial market by surprise by
announcing that the official overnight borrowing rate would be cut
to 5.5 percent from 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed the day's trading here at 75.81
U.S. cents, down from yesterday's close of 75.89 after trading in
a range of 75.65 to 75.88 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
If the U.S. job data proves to be stronger than expected, it
would boost expectations of an increase in interest rates in the
United States, resulting in a fall in the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 87.86 yen, down from 88.39, and
at 1.3099 marks, down from 1.3158.  
</P>
</TEXT>
