<HEADLINE> Indian Govt Encourages Investment in Road Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government has decided
to give 100 percent income tax exemption for the first five years
and 30 percent for 20 years to attract private sector
participation in the road building sector.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Surface Transport T.G. Venkatraman, who announced
this decision here today, said that the Cabinet Committee on
Infrastructure also decided to allow the National Highway
Authority of India (NHAI) to provide capital grants up to 40
percent for build, operate and transfer (BOT) projects for
national highways to enable leveraging of private investment in
this sector.
</P>
<P>
It was also decided to exempt from customs duty special heavy
machinery required for speeding up highway construction, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, of the 2.03 million kilometers road
length in the country, only half is surfaced and most of the
unsurfaced roads are non-motorable. The national highway network
of about 34,000 kilometers has only 358 km four-lane roads while
6,674 km are of single intermediate lanes.
</P>
<P>
Road quality standards too have not kept pace with changes in
vehicle and freight technologies as they are designed only for
single axle vehicles with axle load up to 8.20 tons. Poor quality
of roads and heavy congestion result in longer turnaround of
vehicles and lead to higher transportation costs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
