<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coli 0-157 Bacteria Resistant to Drugs Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The 0-157 strain of E. Coli bacteria
has been found to be resistant to the Japanese Health Ministry's
prescribed antibiotic fosfomycin last July at the start of a food
poisoning outbreak, Kyodo News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Researchers from the Pharmacology Department at the Yamaguchi
University Faculty of Medicine confirmed the drug-resistant
properties of the bacillus, which are thought to develop inside
the colon, in experiments conducted in open air.
</P>
<P>
The researchers will announce the results of their study at a
Japan Society of Chemotherapy meeting, which will open in Tokyo on
June 12.
</P>
<P>
The antibiotic fosfomycin was prescribed for use by the
ministry to treat those infected in last summer's mass poisoning
in Sakai, Osaka prefecture, and was considered to have been highly
effective.
</P>
<P>
The Yamaguchi research team cultivated E. Coli bacteria from
six people infected last July and compared the effectivity of
seven kinds of antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
By mixing nutrient fluids and replicating inside the test tube
conditions similar to those found in the human body,
pharmacologists discovered that fosfomycin lost its germicidal
effect in all six patients and failed to inhibit replication of
the bacteria in one of the six patients.
</P>
<P>
An E. coli 0-157 poisoning epidemic claimed 12 lives and made
more than 10,000 people ill in Japan last July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Young Musicians To Play At Historic Moment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOMG KONG, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The summer of 1997 means
something special for 21-year-old Joseph Kam Ho Pang, a musical
student who has played violin and viola for more than one decade.
</P>
<P>
Joseph is happy to be chosen for the third time as a violinist
of the Asian Youth Orchestra (AYO) -- a summer-camp program which
selects 102 outstanding young musicians each year from 11 Asia
countries and regions for six-week rehearsal and performance tour.
</P>
<P>
What makes him happier is that he, together with other members
of the AYO, will perform on two occasions marking the return of
Hong Kong to its motherland on July 1, 1997. They will perform the
premiere of a new composition titled Symphony 1997, written
specially for the historic handover by Chinese composer Tan Dun.
</P>
<P>
"I'm so happy that I can perform on such a special occasion. I
can witness the history. I feel I'm part of the history," said the
young man.
</P>
<P>
"As a Chinese, I'm proud to see that China can take back Hong
Kong and the colonial rule will come to an end," he added.
</P>
<P>
Joseph is not alone in having a sense of pride. As a matter of
fact, 11 Hong Kong students have been selected to the AYO this
summer and will give the special performance at the historic
moment. They all come from the Hong Kong Academy for Performing
Arts.
</P>
<P>
Apart from those Chinese students from Hong Kong, the AYO has
chosen 22 students from well-known conservatories across China,
and 11 students from Taipei.
</P>
<P>
"We're all proud of playing 'Symphony 1997' on the significant
occasion," said AYO's Executive Director Richard Pontzious, who is
 now busy arranging the rehearsal to start on June 9 in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The students will take part in a three-week rehearsal camp in
Malaysia before they come to Hong Kong on the eve of the
handover. On July 1, they will cooperate with the world-famous
cello soloist Yo-Yo Ma to play part of "Symphony 1997" first at
the founding ceremony of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR), and then on the bank of the Victoria Harbor to
accompany the spectacular fireworks show in the evening. Composer
Tan Dun will conduct the two performances.
</P>
<P>
Symphony 1997, divided into three movements -- Heaven, Earth
and Mankind, is a large scale choral and orchestral work, which
combines the voice of a 200-children choir, the sound of a set of
2,500-year-old Chinese chime called Bianzhong and the melody of
cello by YO-Yo Ma. It took Chinese composer Tan Dun almost one
year to complete the work.
</P>
<P>
The 55-minute work will be staged on July 4 at the Hong Kong
Cultural Center, said the executive director. On the following
day, the AYO will perform Symphony 1997 at the Great Hall of the
People in Beijing, raising the curtain of a ten-day tour in six
Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
Joseph has never been to Beijing, and now he expects to
perform in the capital of China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
