<HEADLINE> Primakov on Russia-NATO Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Evgeny
Primakov said here today that the document signed last month in
Paris between Russia and NATO will contribute to "real
international stabilization."
</P>
<P>
Addressing the on-going Conference on Disarmament, Primakov
said that the substance of the Founding Act "reflected the
political will of leaders of the largest nations in Europe and
America to take into account security and cooperation interests of
each other for the sake of stability in the world."
</P>
<P>
However, he said that Russia is still opposed to NATO's
eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
The NATO enlargement "can bring about new dividing lines in
Europe which we started to intensively eliminate in the post Cold
War era", he said.
</P>
<P>
The reason why Russia decided to sign the Founding Act with
NATO "is precisely to minimize the negative effects of such an
enlargement," he added.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said he hoped that the practical implementation of the
principles and the "code of conduct" laid down in the Act will
help to enhance security in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Primakov is in Geneva for a one-day official visit to the
United Nations Office at Geneva. 
</P>
</TEXT>
