<HEADLINE> Syrian Vice President Meets Lebanese Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Vice President Abdel Halim
Khaddam and Lebanese leaders today exchanged views on the
establishment of an Arab economic bloc and regional issues.
</P>
<P>
Khaddam, accompanied by Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk Sharaa,
held a meeting in the Beirut Presidential Palace with Lebanese
President Elias Hrawi, Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and Foreign
Minister Farez Boueiz.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed Lebanese leaders the outcomes of his recent
tour of Arab capitals in the Gulf and north Africa.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the meeting, the Syrian vice president announced
that his talks with the Lebanese leaders dealt with a Middle East
economic conference, which is due to be held in Doha, Qatar, next
November, and a Turkish-Israeli coalition.
</P>
<P>
He said that they discussed ways "to establish an Arab
economic bloc which will bring the inter-Arab relations into a
new phase and put the cooperations between the Arab states on the
correct path."
</P>
<P>
Khaddam stressed that the responses to Syrian proposals, which
he received during the recent tour of Arab countries, were "very
good," but he did not specify what the proposals he has been
marketing to the Arab leaders.
</P>
<P>
On the current Turkish incursion into Iraq in pursuit of
Kurdish separatists, the Syrian leader noted that what is
happening in northern Iraq "not only concerns Iraq, but concerns
all the Arab states as a whole."
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish-Israeli partnership is a security, political and
economic partnership which is aimed at controlling the region,
aimed at Arab territories and aimed at Arab resources," the
Syrian leader claimed.
</P>
<P>
"We all should do what we can do to press Turkey to change its
policy because this policy is not in the interests of Turkey and
does not help realize the security and stability in the region,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Khaddam denied any assistances have been sent from Syria to
the Kurdistan Worker's Party (PKK), which is struggling for an
autonomy in southeast Turkey, and said that "Syria wants to
maintain good relations with all its Islamic neighbors." 
</P>
