<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao to Stage Portuguese-Style Bullfighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Macao is to stage another round of
Portuguese-style bullfighting in September and October this year
following a similar act in February last year.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen bullfighters, including one woman, 24 bulls and three
horses will arrive from Portugal for the event, which will cost 5
million patacas (about 632,900 U.S. dollars), the newspaper Macao
Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese matadors will fight the bulls on September 27 and 28
and October 1, 4, and 5 as a way to attract more tourists to the
territory, coinciding with an international fireworks display to
be held at the time.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the special suits for matadors and fighting
tools will be on show in the territory to let viewers learn more
about the Portuguese tradition.
</P>
<P>
Organizers said the main difference between Portuguese-style
fighting and Spanish-style fighting is that the bulls in
Portuguese fighting are not killed on the spot, but butchered
later.
</P>
<P>
Last year's bullfighting attracted thousands of viewers, mostly
from Hong Kong. Organizers of this year's event believe the
upcoming bullfighting will also be a success.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
