<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibar to Expand Internal Revenue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Pei Shanqin)
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Zanzibar government will
during 1997/98 fiscal year put more thrust on increasing revenue
from internal sources to reduce dependence on external donors.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the 1997/98 government budget proposal to the House
of Representatives in the town of Zanzibar on Wednesday, Minister
of Finance Amina Ali said increased inland revenue would cover
budget deficit and finance recurrent and development votes.
</P>
<P>
She said the government will continue to implement policies
aimed at strengthening the economy, building internal foundation
for self-management without dependence on external revenue.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the house that over-dependence on external
financial sources was improper and likely to risk sacrificing the
nation's integrity and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
She said projections for development programs were not
realized because several donors suspended aid to the Isles.
</P>
<P>
The Donors accuse Zanzibar of a "poor human rights record", a
claim mounted shortly after the 1995 general elections in which
the ruling Revolutionary Party (CCM) presidential candidate,
Salmin Amour, defeated Seif Shariff Hamad of the opposition Civic
United Front (CUF).
</P>
<P>
"Government individuals, private enterprises and individuals
must work tirelessly to achieve this objective - and today, not
tomorrow," Ali stressed.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the government was reviewing all sources
possibility of increasing them, adding that the government will
continue with efforts to collect revenue through the Zanzibar
Revenue Board.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government will put a stop to all tax
exemptions which are unjustified by investment law and customs
regulations.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, during the 1997/98 fiscal year, the
government is expected to collect 40.5 billion Tanzanian
Shillings (about 67.5 million U.S. Dollars) from various taxes
including those from the tourism and petroleum sectors.
</P>
<P>
She said in the new financial year, all other rates of
existing taxes will not be reviewed upwards due to poor income
and low standard of living of the islanders.
</P>
<P>
The minister also told the house that in the new fiscal year,
the government expenditure will be 55.4 billion Tanzanian
Shillings (about 32.3 million U.S. Dollars), out of which 42.2
billion Tanzanian Shillings (about 70.3 million U.S. Dollars)
will be for recurrent expenditure and 12.8 billion Tanzanian
Shillings (about 21.3 million U.S. Dollars) will be for
development budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
