<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Assists E. Africa's Fight Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government has
provided about 8.6 million U.S. Dollars to Kenya, Tanzania and
Uganda for the biological control of the water hyacinth in Lake
Victoria, the second largest fresh water lake in the world.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total sum, Kenya will receive 2.4 million Dollars
and the rest will be shared between the other two eastern African
countries, Jim Lindsay, the Australian deputy High Commissioner,
was quoted by today's Daily Nation newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Biological means of controlling the water weed still remain
some of the most effective and cheapest, he said Wednesday at a
seminar on training facilitators in beetle-rearing in Kisumu,
Kenya's northern city bordering the lake.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Agricultural Research Institute (KARI) Deputy Director
A.M. Mailu said at the seminar that the KARI has released 10,000
beetles into Lake Victoria beaches as part of the process of
eradicating the water hyacinth.
</P>
<P>
The hyacinth now covers an area of more than 70,000 hectares
of the Kenyan part of the lake.
</P>
<P>
About 60 million neochetina beetles, an acclaimed natural
enemy of the hyacinth, would be released in at least 150 stations
on the Kenyan side this year, making Kenya the first in the east
African region to advocate the use of beetles.
</P>
<P>
The water hyacinth weed, one of the fastest-spreading plants
in the earth, was first noticed in Lake Victoria in 1980s, but
did not pose a significant problem until 1990s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
