<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German GDP Up 0.5 Percent in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Germany's gross domestic product was
up 0.5 percent in the first three months this year over the last
quarter of 1996, and 1.4 percent higher than that in the same
period last year, the Federal Statistics Office said today.
</P>
<P>
Working days totaled less than in the first quarter of 1996
due to the earlier coming of Easter holidays, otherwise the
annualized growth rate may have been even higher, the office said.
</P>
<P>
"This working days factor could have accounted for more than
one percentage point of economic growth," it said.
</P>
<P>
The 0.5 percent quarter-to-quarter growth indicated an economic
upturn after zero growth at the end of 1996. This also disproves
recent stagnation projection by the German Economic Research
Institute in Berlin that zero growth or even a negative 0.25
percent would be seen in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Imports grew by 3.9 percent. Exports registered a real 6.8
percent increase compared with a year earlier, remaining the only
factor that boosts economy.
</P>
<P>
According to Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt, real job
creation can only be expected after the pickup of investments and
domestic demand in the country, which has suffered record
unemployment this year.
</P>
<P>
The data published today by the office showed that compared
with the first quarter of 1996, domestic demand grew only by 0.6
percent, while capital equipment investments by just 2.2 percent
and construction investments by 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Employment went 528,000 lower than in the first quarter of last
year, while a 2.9 percent increase was registered in labor
productivity, according to the statistics office.
</P>
<P>
Western Germany's annual GDP growth was just 1.2 percent in the
first quarter, compared with the 1.8 percent growth rate in the
last quarter of 1996. In the eastern area, the annualized growth
rate was 2.8 percent, the same as the last quarter of 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
