<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Overseas Investments Help Beijing's Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Since China first opened its doors
to the outside world 19 years ago, overseas funds have played an
annually increasing role in Beijing's economic development.
</P>
<P>
To a significant degree, foreign funding is responsible for
invigorating Beijing, a local source said, adding that from 1979
to 1996, a total of 10.2 billion US dollars had been actually
used, accounting for 29.96 percent of the entire fixed assets'
investment in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
According to Yi Xiqun, director of the municipal economy and
foreign trade commission, there were 12,845 overseas-funded
enterprises in the capital as of this April.
</P>
<P>
He said that the combined contractual overseas investment had
reached more than 20 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
As many as 279 multinational companies have put their money
into 366 projects in Beijing, with the direct investment totaling
2.9 billion US dollars, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Yi, 132 of the 500 largest multinational companies
in the world have entered the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the city's total gross domestic product
(GDP) for 1996 was 97.2 billion yuan (12 billion US dollars) more
than in 1991, 36 percent of which came from overseas-funded
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of GDP from overseas-funded enterprises in the
city's total GDP increased from 12.9 percent in 1991 to 27.3
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Most of these investments have aided Beijing's tertiary sector.
</P>
<P>
"They have contributed a great deal to the internationalization
of Beijing and helped to establish a modern, open and prosperous
image for the ancient city," a local source commented.
</P>
<P>
Also, the overseas funds are believed to have improved the
city's industrial structure, promoted the development of Beijing's
now-booming hi-tech sector, and introduced advanced technology and
management experience to the capital.
</P>
<P>
Among all the overseas-funded enterprises currently in Beijing,
81 percent have introduced "advanced technology and management
experience" into their operations.
</P>
<P>
"The existence of overseas-funded enterprises has largely
filled the gap between Chinese enterprises and their overseas
counterparts in terms of technology and management," a local
economic observer said.
</P>
<P>
The overseas funds in Beijing have hastened the development of
the city's real estate sector and the infrastructure construction
as well.
</P>
<P>
At present, 458 real estate development projects have been
approved to receive a total of 5.03 billion US dollars in overseas
funding. The construction areas will total an estimated 27 million
sq m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Overseas Investments Help Beijing's Economy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Along the well-known commercial street of Wangfujing, and the
"financial street" in the Xicheng District, as much as 30 to 35
percent of the total overseas investment was channeled into real
estate development.
</P>
<P>
On Beijing's Chongwaidajie, one of the capital's main streets,
the entire 516 million yuan (64 million US dollars) in
infrastructure renovation costs were provided by the New World
group company from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's foreign trade has also been expanded and optimized
partly due to the introduction and use of overseas funds.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, overseas-funded enterprises in Beijing exported 810
million US dollars-worth of goods, making up 34.46 of the
capital's total export volume. And 82 percent of the hi-tech
products export volume came from overseas-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
There are now 4,586 overseas-funded enterprises in Beijing,
with 362,800 employees.
</P>
<P>
Last year these businesses paid 3.5 billion yuan (400 million
US dollars) in taxes, accounting for 19.7 percent of the total
industrial and commercial tax income in Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
