<HEADLINE> Pakistan Warns Against Indian Missile Deployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has warned that India's
deployment of medium-range ballistic missiles near the Pakistani
border has created "a dangerous security environment."
</P>
<P>
"The Indian action bears the potential of unleashing a
ballistic missile race in South Asia," a Foreign Office spokesman
today quoted Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan as saying in a
letter to U.S. Secretary of State Madeline Albright Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The threat posed by this escalatory action would leave us no
choice but to take appropriate countermeasures," the minister said
in the letter.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman told a weekly news briefing here that the foreign
minister has also pointed out that "India appears to have been
encouraged by the discriminatory American legislation against
Pakistan that has resulted in a serious military imbalance in the
region."
</P>
<P>
As regards the reported cooperation among Thailand, Bangladesh,
India and Sri Lanka, the spokesman said, "It is the sovereign
right of every state to enter into such cooperation with other
countries if they deem it necessary for the economic well-being of
their peoples."
</P>
<P>
"We do not think it will in any way affect the cooperation
among the SAARC countries," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
