<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diplomacy Active in S. Leone Amid Peacekeeping Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Chang Yong)
</P>
<P>
LAGOS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- While west Africa's peacekeeping
existence is being reinforced in coup-torn Sierra Leone, a
diplomatic drive has been launched by Nigeria to prevent external
assistance for coupists and rebels in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports in Lagos said Nigeria on Tuesday sent from
its military base in Liberia at least four helicopters packed
with heavily armed soldiers to Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a four-man Nigerian military team arrived in
Freetown Wednesday night to assess the situation.
</P>
<P>
They are reported to join senior ECOMOG commanders for talks
with the coup leaders of the country.
</P>
<P>
Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings has also sent his deputy
foreign minister and chief of defense staff to Freetown for peace
talks with Sierra Leone's coup leaders.
</P>
<P>
In an address in Accra, capital of Ghana, to mark the 18th
anniversary of the 1979 coup that first brought him to power,
President Rawlings said: "The reasons for the coup in Sierra
Leone are unjustified and we all back the action of Nigeria."
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to examine all avenues to settling the
crisis, with emphasis on a negotiated settlement," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time Rawlings had commented publicly on the
May 25 coup that toppled Sierra Leone's elected government led by
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
This coincided with earlier reports that the military junta
led by Major Jonny Koromah in Sierra Leone had announced the
release of all 300 Nigerian soldiers allegedly held as hostages
to discourage the military intervention.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted a state radio broadcast in Freetown on
Wednesday as saying: "Their release is a gesture of goodwill as
the Armed Forces Revolutionary Council (the junta's ruling organ)
is exploring all avenues to bring the situation to a peaceful
end."
</P>
<P>
It said that food and other logistics were provided for the
Nigerian soldiers, including 13 military officers, as they were
escorted back to their base.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian military denied the men's capture.
</P>
<P>
Two days after the coup, the ECOMOG force led by Nigeria
launched an attack on the coupists with an aim to restore the
legitimate civilian government of the country.
</P>
<P>
The military intervention has won wide support from the
international community, including the United Nations and the
Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone, a former British colony racked by civil war
since 1991, has suffered three coups in five years. It is one of
the world's poorest countries despite a wealth of quality
diamonds and other mineral resources.
</P>
<P>
The coup leaders have accused President Kabbah of failing to
consolidate a peace accord signed last November with Foday
Sankoh, leader of the rebel Revolutionary United Front, and of
failing to pacify ethnic conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh, reportedly in detention in Nigeria, has been appointed
by Major Koromah as his vice-chairman and is said to call on his
men to support the coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
