<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> West Africa May Adopt Common Currency by Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Wang Yongkang)
</P>
<P>
LAGOS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The 16 Member countries of the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) may adopt a
common currency by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper the Punch reported today that the issue will
be discussed by ECOWAS heads of states at a summit scheduled to
be held in Abuja, the Nigerian capital, next month.
</P>
<P>
David Asante, head of Monetary Cooperation and Payment
Relations at the ECOWAS Secretariat, confirmed that the year 2000
will be the time for adoption of the common currency.
</P>
<P>
The idea emerged from a meeting of the central banks of ECOWAS
countries in Nouakchott, Mauritania, in 1987.
</P>
<P>
The year 1992 was earlier set for the goal but it was not
achieved because of the unpreparedness of member countries.
</P>
<P>
As a prelude to the goal of a single currency, the Council of
ECOWAS Ministers of Finance has come out with "indicators of
convergence" to be observed by members.
</P>
<P>
The council demands that member countries keep a single-digit
inflation rate and a government deficit not more than three
percent of their Gross Domestic Product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Member countries have also let their exchange rate be
determined by the market and subject to year-to-year variations
not more than five percent.
</P>
<P>
Of the 16 member states, only Nigeria, Ghana and Guinea Bissau
are yet to achieve the acceptable level of inflation, while
Guinea Bissau, Togo and Sierra Leone are yet to meet the
three-percent GDP deficit index.
</P>
<P>
Eight ECOWAS members countries in the French-speaking
countries are already using a single currency, the CFA Franc
which is tied to the French Franc.
</P>
<P>
Liberia is using the U.S. Dollar, while other member countries
have their own currencies, the exchange rates of which are mostly
under full official control instead of being subjected to the
market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
