<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Photo Exhibition on Hong Kong Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A two-week long Photo
Exhibition -- "Hong Kong: Its History and Today" opened here today
in connection with the resumption of exercise of sovereignty over
Hong Kong by the People's Republic of China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Minister of Culture, Arts and Tourism Sabbaruddin
Chik and Chinese ambassador to Malaysia Qian Jinchang jointly
officiated the exhibition organized by the Chinese Embassy in
Malaysia with the assistance of the National Museum of Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Nearly one hundred photos are put on display, introducing Hong
Kong's history, present situation and the process of Hong Kong's
return to China and revealing an even more beautiful tomorrow for
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Sabbaruddin said on the occasion that "the efforts put in
organizing such an exhibition show the seriousness of the Chinese
people in strengthening the heart to heart relationship with the
Malaysian people."
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and China have enjoyed friendly relationship since
long time ago, he said, adding the ties between the two countries
have become closer and closer in economic, political, cultural and
educational fields.
</P>
<P>
He sincerely hoped that this exhibition will further enhance
future cultural exchanges between Malaysia and China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ambassador expressed the hope that the exhibition
will help friends in Malaysia better understand Hong Kong and the
great significance of implementing the principle of "one country,
two systems" in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Qian said the exhibition itself presents one aspect of the
Chinese nation's sufferings during the past more than 150 years
after the signing of the Treaty of Nanking which ceded Hong Kong
to Britain.
</P>
<P>
He said the resumption of exercise of sovereignty over Hong
Kong by the People's Republic of China will wipe out the
humiliation that the Chinese nation suffered over the past 100
years and more.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his belief that "after Hong Kong's return to the
motherland, with the principle of 'one country, two systems' and
the legal guarantee of the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, Hong Kong will definitely have a more
beautiful, more prosperous and brighter future."  
</P>
</TEXT>
