<HEADLINE> EU Envoy Ends Visit to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU) Mideast envoy
Miguel Moratinos left here this morning, wrapping up his short
visit to Egypt that is aimed to infuse vigor to the stalled peace
process.
</P>
<P>
During his one-day stay here, Moratinos held separate talks
with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa on the latest developments of the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Following the meetings, Moratinos said that "there is some
breakthrough, but there is still much work to be done."
</P>
<P>
Moratinos said the EU supports the current Egyptian peace moves
and agrees with Egyptian officials that Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu has "a desire for riding out the current peace
plight."
</P>
<P>
But Moratinos stressed that without the Americans it is
impossible to weather out the ongoing peace crisis.
</P>
<P>
He added that he will head for Washington to meet with
U.S. Mideast peace coordinator Dennis Ross to exchange views on
overcoming the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters after meeting the EU emissary on Wednesday
night, Moussa did not say whether Moratinos forwarded to the
Egyptian leader any European initiative reportedly to be unveiled
in the upcoming EU summit in Amsterdam, Holland.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos has been shuttling in the region as part of the
European endeavors to revive the deadlocked peace march and
restart the Palestinian-Israeli negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
