<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guizhou Launches Drive to Invite More Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guizhou Province
recently launched a drive to invite investment for its 1,000-odd
projects, and scored big at the latest investment and trade fair
held here.
</P>
<P>
According to a local source, contracts have already been signed
for 13 projects, including funding of 95 million US dollars by an
American company for a coking plant, and an investment of 26.5
million US dollars by a Japanese firm to manufacture car parts.
</P>
<P>
Companies from Canada and Hong Kong have also signed contracts
for establishing joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
So far, deals with investment totaling 240 million US dollars
and over one billion yuan have been sealed.
</P>
<P>
The source said that the projects needing funding involve the
sectors of energy, raw materials, tourism, real estate and the
processing industry.
</P>
<P>
The power sector alone plans to attract a total investment of
500 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou is an economically under-developed province. However,
it has rich resources and huge potential. To date, more than 1,000
foreign-funded enterprises have been set up in the province.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the province approved the establishment of 82
foreign-funded enterprises, with actual investment hitting 106
million US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
