<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 09:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-Israel Strategic Talks Under Way in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Senior U.S. and Israeli
military officials are holding their biannual strategic talks in
Netanya, north of Tel Aviv, against the background of stalled
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The two-day talks, which started Wednesday, focuses on the
needs of the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) for "qualitative edge"
in the future, local English daily The Jerusalem Post reported
today.
</P>
<P>
David Ivry, special adviser to Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai, is representing Israel and the U.S. is being
represented by Assistant Secretary of State Ted MacNamara,
accompanied by officials from the State Department and
Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has long committed itself to maintaining Israel's
strategic edge over the Arabs. Israel has used the commitment in
its requests for advanced military technology and its opposition
to sales by the U.S. of advanced weapons and satellite
photographs to Arab states.
</P>
<P>
Israel has also sought U.S. help in preventing what it
believed rival states, Iran in particular, in the Middle East
from obtaining non-conventional weapons and nuclear knowhow.
</P>
<P>
The change of Iran's leadership is also a major topic in the
discussions. Senior Israeli sources are very pleased over the
fact that last week, U.S. President Bill Clinton publicly defined
clear conditions for improving relations with Iran, according to
a report of Hebrew newspaper Haaretz.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made it clear that the U.S. will judge Iran according
to the degree of change in its actions on three international
fronts: weapons proliferation, terror and the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
At the first press conference after his election, Iranian
president-elected Mohammad Khatami said that Iran will not
intervene in the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nanjing Issues Regular Reports On Cleanness of Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Nanjing, capital of east China's
Jiangsu province, now reports the city's atmospheric conditions
weekly through the media to arouse people's awareness of a
cleaner air.
</P>
<P>
The city's atmosphere has been lightly polluted according to
the first atmospheric quality report issued on May 23.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing is one of the first group of cities across China that
began to publicly report on their atmospheric quality.
</P>
<P>
Most residents of the city has noticed the new report,
expressing their support through telephone, and leaders of major
enterprises discharging pollutants into the atmosphere have become
more aware of their social responsibilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
