<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: An Untiring Psychologist in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- At the age of 70, Prof. Chen
Zhongshun still works 16-hours a day.
</P>
<P>
The first person in China to set up a telephone hotline for
psychological counseling, Chen's daily workload consists of dozens
of phone calls and correspondence with those seeking his
specialized help.
</P>
<P>
He regularly holds consultations at hospitals and contributes
articles to 12 magazines across the country. But to the
hard-working professor, the hotline, which is affiliated with
China's Association for Suicide Prevention, is his pride and joy.
</P>
<P>
"I would give up anything but the hotline -- it is the main
communication channel between me and society," he says.
</P>
<P>
Chen, formerly a professor with Tianjin Medical College, has a
degree in psychology with an emphasis in mental health. Upon
retirement 10 years ago, he publicized his home phone number,
offering it as a means of assistance in a society that until only
recently regarded frank talk about mental illness as taboo.
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade, Chen's hotline help has saved the lives
of 180 persons, mended 125 troubled families, and successfully
handled 1,200 cases involving people with serious mental
problems. Over 100,000 persons from all around China, including
some in Hong Kong and Taiwan, have sought the professor's
professional advice.
</P>
<P>
Chen has over the years developed numerous forms of counseling,
including group therapy, to tackle the problems of his patients in
the shortest time possible, which usually varies from three days
to two weeks. And his hotline has expanded to three telephones
lines, staffed by 12 volunteers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: An untiring Psychologist in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"People had no idea what `psychological counseling' was ten
years ago." he recalled. "The hotline was greeted with rumors
rather than understanding at first."
</P>
<P>
"Counseling then was confined to marital and sexual problems,
which in the traditional Chinese way of thinking was nearly taboo
even for discussion between close friends, let alone something to
talk about with a stranger on the phone," Chen explained.
</P>
<P>
"But China has been undergoing unprecedented changes," said the
professor.
</P>
<P>
To his gratification, his pioneering work has initiated a boom
in counseling services in China, with hotlines and organizations
providing consultations mushrooming throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Chen pointed out that psychological counseling has wide room
for development in China, as people of all age groups are becoming
more and more burdened by increasing job and family pressures.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey, 12 to 15 out of every 1,000 people in
China suffer from some form of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
Chen stressed that China still is short of professionals in the
field of psychological counseling.
</P>
<P>
"There are some who are taking the job who actually know little
about it," he pointed out. "We have a long way to go before
psychological counseling becomes a well-developed social sector in
China."  
</P>
</TEXT>
