<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 13 Cities To Weekly Report On Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- China's major cities have made
preparations to report weekly on their atmospheric quality,
announced Wan Bentai, head of China's Environmental Monitoring
Station.
</P>
<P>
The weekly reporting system will begin July 5 in ten
cities: Beijing, Shanghai, Tianjin, Shenyang, Xian, Guangzhou,
Wuhan, Chongqing, Nanjing, and Hangzhou. Three other cities,
Dalian, Xiamen, and Zhuhai, will follow suit.
</P>
<P>
Meteorological stations in the 13 cities and the Atmosphere
Research Institute under the Chinese Academy of Sciences have
promised to render support to the project.
</P>
<P>
The 13 cities have begun trial reporting since April 4, listing
the atmosphere pollution index, key polluting sources, and
influence upon human health as major reporting items.
</P>
<P>
Sulfur dioxide, chemical compounds of oxygen and nitrogen, and
the amount of suspended substances, are listed as major indicators
of atmosphere's quality.
</P>
<P>
An average of five monitoring stations should be built in each
city and nine to ten will be set up in Beijing, and the weekly
report will be publicized through local media and submitted to
China's Environmental Monitoring Station to be compiled and
issued. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
