<HEADLINE> Beijing City Government to Raise Outlays in Public Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Beijing City will give an
additional 100 million yuan to public health, Beijing Mayor Jia
Qinglin said at a recent conference on health work.
</P>
<P>
The outlay will be spent in the fields of disease prevention,
health promotion, rural public health, medical research and
teaching, health-related law-enforcement, improving the first-aid
system, blood management, and traditional Chinese medicine.
</P>
<P>
Jia noted that public health is a public welfare for which the
government holds major responsibilities. Over the past two
decades, the municipal government has been raising the amount of
money in the sector, but practical demands have yet to be met.
</P>
<P>
Jia called on governments at various levels to consider public
health needs while making their budgets. And the increase rate of
public health budget should not be lower than the increase rate of
fiscal expenditures.
</P>
<P>
The mayor said that individuals and businesses or institutions
should also undertake a certain amount of medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, appropriations from the city
government only make up ten percent of the expenditures in
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government also plans to set aside money to
relieve the housing difficulties and raise the salaries of the
city's medical workers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
