<HEADLINE> Indian PM Arrives in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister I. K.
Gujral arrived here today on a three-day official visit to Nepal
at the invitation of his Nepali counterpart Lokendra Bahadur
Chand.
</P>
<P>
Gujral was greeted by the Nepali prime minister at the airport
amid a brief welcome ceremony with a 21-gun salute.
</P>
<P>
Gujral told reporters at the airport that his Nepal visit, the
first bilateral one after he assumed the office as prime minister
in April, would further strengthen the existing cordial relations
between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
India and Nepal are committed to seeking closer ties in
economic cooperation and other areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the two prime ministers will hold official
talks on various bilateral matters later today.
</P>
<P>
They are also scheduled to sign two agreements on power trade
and air service respectively today, according to Nepali official
sources.
</P>
<P>
The power trading agreement, which was first initialed early
last year in Mumbai, provides Nepal the access of its electricity
to the Indian market.
</P>
<P>
While the air service agreement will allow Nepali and India
marginally increase their seat capacity to each other's country
from the present 4,000 seats every week, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, documents of the ratification of a bilateral treaty
on the development of a common border river will be exchanged
between the two governments during Gujral's stay in Kathmandu.
</P>
<P>
Under the treaty signed in New Delhi last year, Nepal and India
will jointly launch a 6,480-megawatt multi-purpose hydro project
on the Mahakali river, about 450 km west of here.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Gujral will call on Nepali King Birendra and meet
with other high ranking government officials and major political
party leaders.
</P>
<P>
He is also expected to lay the foundation stone for a Kathmandu
hospital expansion project assisted by the Indian government and
address the Nepal World Affairs Council here before leaving for
home on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Among Gujral's entourage during his current Nepal visit are
Minister of State for Power S. Venugopalachari and other senior
government official.
</P>
<P>
Gujral's visit is the first by an Indian prime minister to this
 country since 1992.  
</P>
</TEXT>
