<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia to Set Bottom-Line for Family Income </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, June 5 (Xinhua) -- "The money came at the nick of time
and I'm grateful to the government," said Chen Qingsheng, a
factory layoff who recently received subsidiaries from the local
government.
</P>
<P>
Chen was laid off by his factory two years ago and has since
then lived by picking odds and ends from refuse heaps to support
his family.
</P>
<P>
In the first four months this year, 2,394 families in Hohhot,
the regional capital of the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, have
received government money for poor families.
</P>
<P>
The regional government plans to set a minimum income of local
families living in the region's 12 cities effective July 1,
according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai was the first city in the country to adopt the
bottom-line system and now 156 Chinese cities follow the
policy. Hohhot and Baotou cities are the first two in Inner
Mongolia.  
</P>
