<HEADLINE> Israel Wins Deal to Upgrade Helicopters for Poland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli arms consortium has
won a 600-million-U.S. dollar deal to upgrade about 100
helicopters for Poland, The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The consortium, which comprises of Elbit Ltd., El-Op
Industries and the Armament Development Authority, gained the
deal in fierce competition with a group led by the U.S. Boeing
company and several European sub-contractors.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few months, the U.S.-led group applied heavy
pressure on Warsaw that appeared to link the deal to acceptance
of Poland into the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
But Polish Defense Ministry informed the Israeli consortium
recently that it had won the competition, the report quoted El-Op
President Jacob Toren as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We are waiting for the decision to be realized. The
announcement has been delayed," Toren said, adding that the delay
 might stem from Warsaw's fear about Washington's strong reaction
 to the choice. Others expected the announcement to be made in
the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
"There has been an agreement, although no contract has yet
been signed. The signing, however, could take place very soon,"
an Elbit source was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
But an Elbit spokeswoman said she could neither confirm nor
deny the Polish decision.
</P>
<P>
Israel entered the competition for the upgrade of the
Polish-designed Huzar helicopters in 1994. The upgrade will
involve avionics, missiles and fire-control systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
