<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Wildlife College to Be Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 5 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will officially
launch a wildlife college in September this year for training
conservation managers, local daily Business Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
The college, the first of its kind in the southern African
region, will be situated in the Timbavati area on the boundary of
the Kruger National Park, a well-known natural wild animal
protection area in northeast South Africa bordering Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
"Our fundamental strategy is to create a generation of black
conservation managers," said C. E. Ian Macdonald, an official of
the South African branch of the World-Wide Fund for Nature.
</P>
<P>
"One of the most damaging legacies of apartheid has been the
perception of conservation as a white preserve -- and to change
this we must have black leadership," Macdonald said.
</P>
<P>
On curriculum arrangement, Macdonald said the core program
offered by the college is a two-year modular course, which
consists of road construction and maintenance, rest camp
management, fence line maintenance and constructive interaction
with neighboring communities.
</P>
<P>
It also includes basic business skills, he added.
</P>
<P>
The college will begin operations with a series of short
courses running from July to December. This is a
capacity-building initiative, designed in line with its goal to
upgrade the level of skills in conservation bodies.
</P>
<P>
Each module, normally lasting from five to 20 days, will be
directed at people against a wide range of backgrounds from
senior park scientists to junior rangers, but will focus mainly
on people from previously disadvantaged groups, said the
official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
