<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 08:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese President Orders Security Mobilization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Elias Hrawi has
ordered the mobilization of security forces to suppress
"lawlessness" reminiscent of the civil war years, the Daily Star
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The order came following a call for civil disobedience made by
a Lebanese Shiite extremist and threats against U.S. targets made
from Beirut by a Kurdish leader whose separatist fellows are
currently fighting tens of thousands Turkish troops in northern
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Opening a weekly cabinet session in the Beirut Presidential
Place Wednesday night, Hrawi disclosed that security agents had
detected a flow of weapons "to known forces in the Beqaa" in the
Shiite Muslim-populated eastern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese president demanded a crackdown by "the
ministries concerned, the security departments and the judiciary,"
said the only English-language daily published in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Although he did not name the recipients of the weapons,
the president was clearly alluding to Sheikh Sobhi Toufeili, a
breakaway Hezbollah leader who is initiating a "hunger
revolution" in the form of civil disobedience for July 4.
</P>
<P>
Nor did Hrawi specify where the arms had come from.
</P>
<P>
The president's rare remarks, described by a government source
as the harshest since the end of the civil war seven years ago,
came after Western diplomats had privately complained about the
threats made from Beirut earlier this week by a commander of the
Kurdish Workers' Party.
</P>
<P>
Commander Hilal Atac held a news conference in Beirut's
southern suburb on Monday in which he threatened to attack
American interests among others in retaliation for Ankara's
campaign against the Kurdish separatists seeking autonomy in
southeast Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Atac spoke of "operations agaisnt Israeli targets in Istanbul
and elsewhere in Turkey and against U.S. enemy's interests."
</P>
<P>
Hrawi said he wanted to uphold public freedoms and
democracy, in which the country takes pride. But, he added,
"trespassing the boundaries of freedom leads to chaos and
ultimately to dictatorship."
</P>
<P>
"In recent days, we've heard and read of a Toufeili here
or a Toufeili there making clear threats to the security of
the state and the safety of its citizens and threatening the
interests of Lebanon and its relations with a friendly
country," Hrawi said.
</P>
<P>
"The media has reported a news conference in south Beirut
during which a Kurdish activist poured threats in all
directions. This does not serve the interests of the state
but is an attempt to inflict harm on the state and
security in the region," he added
</P>
<P>
The president reiterated that the government had made its
position on regional developments clear, denouncing the
Israeli-Turkish military alliance and Ankara's incursion into
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"But this was not a carte blanche for individuals or a
parties to act as they please on Lebanese soil," the
president underlined.
</P>
<P>
"This requires immediate action by the security and judicial
departments in the country in pursuit of anyone posing a threat to
national interests, Lebanon's (foreign) relations and its internal
peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the country's biggest woe was Israel's occupation
of the south, he said: "This, however, does not mean that
resistance against the government or threats to return to the
lawlessness we experienced years back will be tolerated." 
</P>
</TEXT>
