<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EA Airlines Need Common Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Kenya,
Uganda and Tanzania have been urged to finalise arrangements to
adopt an East African (EA) Common Civil Aviation Policy.
</P>
<P>
The chief executives of the national carriers of Kenya, Uganda
and Tanzania made this urgement at the end of their three-day
meeting in Arusha, northern Tanzania, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Arusha-based permanent tripartite
commission for East African Co-operation (EAC) said that adoption
of such a policy would help ease travel between Kenya, Uganda and
Tanzania "and push further the regional co-operation".
</P>
<P>
He noted that streamlining civil aviation rules and adopting
common regulations would help strengthen EA airlines and make
their operations much easier and competitive against outsiders.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also said Kenya Airways has no immediate plans to
participate in the ownership and activities of Ajas. "Alliance
Air is out of context in as far as the East African National
Airlines Co-operation is concerned", said the official.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting it was resolved that the issue of Alliance
Air should be addressed separately among Ajas share holders.
</P>
<P>
On privatisation, the meeting recommended that Kenya Airways'
mode of privatisation, where possible, be used as a guide for the
privatisation of Uganda Airlines and Air Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
On joint use of facilities, the chief executives recommended
that the East African Civil Aviation Academy, Soroti of Uganda
and the East African school of aviation, Nairobi of Kenya be
taken up by member states as regional projects for which donor
assistance could be effective sources.
</P>
<P>
The meeting had also agreed on enhanced efforts towards tariff
harmonisation and schedule co-ordination.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by the Managing Director of the Kenya
Airways, Mr. Brain Davies, Acting General Manager of the Uganda
Airlines, Mr. Dunstan Turinawe and the Acting Managing Director
of the Air Tanzania, Mr. Dominic Rwehunbiza. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
