<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Thailand to Cooperate in Stemming Illegal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand today pledged to
continue to cooperate with Malaysia to stem the influx of illegal
immigrants along their common border.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh, who is here to
attend the 39th Malaysia-Thailand General Border Committee (GBC)
meeting, said today "we are trying our best because we understand
how the problem could burden Malaysia."
</P>
<P>
Chavalit, who is also defense minister, said Thailand is also
facing an illegal immigrant problem, with an estimated 500,000
illegal immigrants in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Thai authorities have tightened checks and issued less than
3,000 transit visas so far this year to foreigners from countries
which required the document to enter Malaysia, Chavalit told a
joint news conference with Malaysian Defense Minister Syed Hamid
Albar who led the Malaysian delegation to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit said Bangladeshi and Myanma nationals were among the
biggest groups of foreigners traveling by land through Thailand to
enter Malaysia in search of work.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid said Malaysia was satisfied with the efforts taken
by Thailand to control the illegal immigrant problem.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian immigration authorities launched a massive
legalization exercise for illegal foreign workers last year but
there are still estimated one million illegal foreign workers in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid said Malaysia and Thailand had agreed to continue
socio-economic activities and social programs along their 647 km
long common border to ensure mutual security, stability and
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
It was decided at the meeting that the next GBC meeting shall
be held in Thailand next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
