<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lin Zexu Foundation to Carry on Combat against Narcotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Xu Jimei, vice-president of the Lin
Zexu Foundation, said that the group will carry forward the battle
against drugs in the name of its founder, who ordered the burning
of some 1,190 tons of opium in Humen in south China's Guangdong
Province in 1840.
</P>
<P>
Lin Zexu was an imperial envoy of the Qing Dynasty government
(1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
The foundation was formally founded on November 6, 1995 in
memory of the man who pioneered the fight against the infiltration
of opium from overseas.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the foundation has received donations worth more
than ten million yuan (1.2 million US dollars), financing some TV
series, publications and various activities in honor of Lin Zexu.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president said the foundation will continue to fund
activities of significance in the fight against drugs, conduct
investigations on the use of drugs among young people, set aside
money to award institutions and individuals who excel in their
work to combat drugs, and promote the research on medicine used in
the rehabilitation of drug addiction.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that there are now as many as one million drug
addicts. Almost 80 percent of them are young people, the figures
show.
</P>
<P>
Cocaine, heroin and the drug "ice" have been discovered in
China, which have the same addictive qualities as opium.
</P>
<P>
The central government has been emphasizing the importance of
the problem. The National People's Congress, China's top
legislature, passed laws in December, 1990, to aid in the
crackdown upon drugs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
