<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0900 GMT, June 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Indian Prime Minister I.K. Gujral left here today
on a three-day visit to Nepal for further enhancing bilateral
relations between the two neighboring countries. Gujral said that
he looked forward to further consolidating the economic dimension
of the Indo-Nepal cooperation.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) has
rejected the plan on the final Israeli-Palestinian settlement put
forward by Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu. PNA
President Yasser Arafat denounced the Netanyahu's plan for
violating the Israeli-Palestinian peace agreements. He added this
was another blow to the deadlocked Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Malaysian Acting Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim
today called upon the ASEAN countries to migrate in stages from
technology recipients to technology providers in the energy sector.
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- Malaysia and Thailand began here today a
three-day meeting to discuss several issues related to their
common border and review past security arrangements. The meeting
is expected to focus on cross-border movement of people and
prevention of smuggling activities along the 647-km long border
shared by the two countries, officials here said.
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- The Myanmar National Commission for Environmental
Affairs (NCEA) marked the World Environment Day here today to
promote environmental education and public awareness in the
country. Myanmar Foreign Minister U Ohn Gyaw gave prizes to those
who won the literary and art competitions on environment-related
subjects. Other activities included exhibitions, television and
radio programs and the distribution of environmental information.
</P>
<P>
ALMA ATA -- A drought-induced fire in the northern part of
Kazakhstan has continued for four days, destroying 5,000 hectares
of conifer forest, the Kazakhstan News Agency said. The fire
remained uncontrolled due to strong wind Wednesday. All residents
in the region have been evacuated.
</P>
<P>
ALMA ATA -- The United States will help Kazakhstan train
military leaders and enhance its military cooperation with
Kazakhstan, a visiting senior U.S. military official said. Kazakh
Defense Minister Mukhstar Aktynbaev said U.S. air force general
Joseph Ralston's visit had nothing to do with the Afghan
situation.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Belarusian President Alexandr Lukashenko has issued a
special order in Minsk, the capital of Belarus, to implement the
Russian-Belarusian Union Treaty. The Russian-Belarusian Union
Treaty, signed by Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Lukashenko
on May 23, included concrete measures to integrate, to an extent,
the former Soviet republics.
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- A hand grenade was flung at Albanian President Sali
Berisha this afternoon but failed to blow up, when he was
campaigning at a mass rally for the upcoming general elections in
the Balkan country. Berisha, campaigning for his Democratic Party,
was speaking at a village rally when a young man threw a grenade
at him from about 15 meters away.
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The Ford Motor Company, the No. 2 American auto
maker, announced Tuesday that it would begin building 250,000
cars, mini-vans and pickup trucks annually that can burn ethanol
or gasoline.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations Security Council today
approved the renewal of Iraqi "oil-for-food deal" for another
period of 180 days beginning on June 8, 1997. In a resolution
adopted unanimously, the Security Council said the renewal of the
"oil-for-food deal" was aimed to alleviate the humanitarian crisis
in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
