<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for Greater Efforts for Treasury Bond Issue (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Two senior financial and banking
officials said here today that greater marketing efforts are
needed to ensure that all of this year's treasury bonds are sold
out in time.
</P>
<P>
"China's treasury bond issue has gone smoothly in the first
half of this year, but to fulfill this year's quota we must work
still harder," Vice-Minister of Finance Liu Jibin said at a
televised meeting today on the floatation of government bonds.
</P>
<P>
The latest official statistics show that a total of more than
85.7 billion yuan in certificate bonds had been sold nationwide by
June 3, about 69.68 percent of the announced amount.
</P>
<P>
The sales of other varieties of treasury bonds have basically
been normal, Liu added.
</P>
<P>
China resumed the practice of issuing treasury bonds in
1981. Its annual issue has been growing rapidly in recent years,
from 19 billion yuan in 1991 to more than 196 billion yuan last
year. This year's government bond issue has been budgeted at more
than 248.6 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, China has offered three batches of treasury
bonds, totaling 60 billion yuan in unregistered bonds and 123
billion yuan in certificate bonds.
</P>
<P>
Shang Fulin, deputy governor of the People's Bank of China, the
central bank, said today that the certificate bonds are likely to
be sold out before the issue closes on October 20, as there are
still more than four months to go.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that sales of the certificate bonds, in
either two, three or five years, have slowed since March, the
first month when they were available.
</P>
<P>
The sales of treasury bonds of different terms are also
unbalanced, he noted, adding that the two-year bonds have turned
out to be the most welcomed while the five-year bonds are the
least favored.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that 86 percent of the 25 billion yuan in
two-year bonds has been snapped up, compared with only 53 percent
for the five-year bonds, which are also valued at 25 billion yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for Greater Efforts for Treasury Bond Issue  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shang attributed the slowdown in bond sales to a capital
diversion to a surging stock market since the start of this year.
</P>
<P>
A huge capital inflow into the stock market is a major factor
affecting the smooth floatation of treasury bonds, he said.
</P>
<P>
The stock indices had soared more than 45 percent each at
China's two stock exchanges in Shanghai and Shenzhen before the
publication of a government regulation banning state enterprises
and listed companies from speculating in stocks on May 12.
</P>
<P>
Shang added that another important reason for the slowdown in
bonds sales is an expanded planned issue of corporate bonds.
</P>
<P>
China has officially set this year's quota of corporate bonds
at 15 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
An widely overlapping availability period of corporate bonds
and treasury bonds in the first half of this year combined with a
higher interest rate for the corporate bonds have made treasury
bonds less attractive to investors, Shang said.
</P>
<P>
Both officials said that more should be done to complete the
floatation of treasury bonds already announced, as another 60
billion yuan in government bonds will have to be issued in the
second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The issuing speed must be accelerated in order to sell out all
bonds when the year ends, they urged.
</P>
<P>
"The floatation of treasury bonds is a important issue that has
a bearing on the overall situation of the economic work," Liu
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shang said that the successful completion of the
treasury bond issues will be in the interest of meeting the
objectives of the financial and monetary policies.
</P>
<P>
It also will help reduce investment risks, the deputy central
bank governor noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
