<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops New Kiwi Preserving Technique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A new technique that can preserve
kiwi for over six months has been developed by Chinese scientists
in Henan province, with aids from United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO).
</P>
<P>
Using a low-pressure ethylene air conditioning process, the
preserving period for kiwi has been extended from three months to
more than six.
</P>
<P>
Kiwi, the so-called "king of fruits," sells well in domestic
and overseas markets. China has an annual kiwi output of 50
million kilograms.
</P>
<P>
However, preservation of the fruit has created a headache for
many kiwi growers, particularly those in east China's Henan
province, who annually lose 30 million yuan (some 3.7 million US
dollars) as a result of problems in the preservation process.
</P>
<P>
The international cooperative project, one of the state's key
scientific research plans listed by the State Science and
Technology Commission, was launched by the Henan provincial
government and the biology institute attached to the Henan Academy
of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The new technique was developed after a 12-year effort.
</P>
<P>
The scientists have so far successfully applied their new
technique to preserve 200,000 kilograms kiwi for six months, a
pilot experiment that could be adopted in preserving large amounts
of the fruit.
</P>
<P>
Henan also built China's first kiwi low-pressure ethylene air
conditioning storehouse in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Comparing with the traditional cold storage or low oxygen
preserving methods, the new technique achieves better result,
is cost-effective, and has a longer preserving period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Building A Forest Park Instead Of Luxury Villas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A forest park in Shaxian County in
Fujian Province, east China, is expected to open this month, now
that the county government vetoed any building of luxury villas on
that spot.
</P>
<P>
The 40-ha Shayang Forest Park has plenty of trees and flowers
and more than 20 scenic spots added, including an outdoor swimming
pool, a children's garden, and a forest dining hall.
</P>
<P>
Local people are eagerly awaiting the opening, but there would
have been no opening at all if county officials had agreed and let
developers have their way in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The widening of national Highway 205 left nearly six ha of open
ground on Fenghuang Mountain, which is near the county seat, so
some departments decided to build luxury villas there. The county
authorities had other ideas however, saying that they would rather
have a place of leisure for ordinary people than a lot more money.
</P>
<P>
So, some experts were invited to do the planning and design a
forest park. Work began on it in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
