<HEADLINE> EU Urged to Make Aid Accessible to African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Economics Association of Zambia
(EAZ) has urged the European union (EU) to channel its aid
through local commercial banks for easy access by peasants of
recipient African countries.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia today quoted EAZ national coordinator Amos
Nakalonga as saying that the EU is currently channeling its aid
through its institutions like the European Investment Bank and
the European Development Fund which make money exclusively
available to commercial farmers.
</P>
<P>
"Since the EU grants and loans are made through these
institutions and aimed at alleviating poverty in the developing
world, it is imperative that funds be channeled through
commercial banks which are easily accessible to all citizens,"
said Nakalonga.
</P>
<P>
"This can be better than the specialized cartels which create
closed clubs, making money exclusively available to commercial
farmers without any trickle to the peasants and deserving
non-government organizations," he added.
</P>
<P>
The EU could consider propping up national chambers of
commerce and other organized groups who will be, as a united
regional body, ready to spearhead negotiations, Nakalonga said.
</P>
</TEXT>
