<HEADLINE> ASEAN Countries Urged to Cooperate in Energy Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Acting Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim today called upon the ASEAN countries to
migrate in stages from technology recipients to technology
providers in the energy sector.
</P>
<P>
There should be more active collaboration among leaders of
industry, academicians and experts from the ASEAN (Association of
Southeast Asian Nations) countries to provide policy guidelines
and blueprint for the sector, he said while opening the first
ASEAN Energy Forum here today.
</P>
<P>
He said a steady economic growth has continued to fuel
impressive energy demand in the ASEAN region, which currently
stands at 140 million tons of oil equivalent (MTOE) and is
expected to increase to 460 MTOE in the year 2020.
</P>
<P>
Anwar urged the ASEAN countries to position themselves
strategically to tap new areas of growth in the energy sector.
</P>
<P>
He said "as a long term project, we also should endeavor to
make the region the regional energy center of excellence with a
fully developed energy sector including all upstream and
downstream activities."
</P>
<P>
To make it a reality, he said, serious attention should be
given towards the development of international connectivity among
the ASEAN countries in terms of the ASEAN grid and for an
integrated ASEAN gas pipeline network.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian leader said one of the key aspects that would
contribute towards the goal and in the process enhance the
region's competitiveness is the development of a modern, secure
and reliable energy system.
</P>
<P>
The future of the energy sector in the ASEAN region would
depend on how the vast opportunities for the local, regional and
global fronts are being capitalized on, he said.
</P>
<P>
The one-day forum, organized by the Association of Independent
Power Producers of Malaysia, was attended by more than 200 experts
and leaders of industry in the energy sector from the ASEAN region
which covers Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, the
Philippines, Thailand and Vietnam as well as Myanmar, Cambodia and
Laos which are set to Join ASEAN in this July.  
</P>
</TEXT>
