<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 06:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Rejects Netanyahu's Plan on Final Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) has rejected the plan on the final
Israeli-Palestinian settlement put forward by Israeli Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Gaza upon returning from an African
tour late Wednesday, PNA President Yasser Arafat denounced the
Netanyahu's plan for violating the Israeli-Palestinian peace
agreements. He added this was another blow to the deadlocked
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu presented the plan to the inner cabinet for
discussion Wednesday, in which he envisioned retaining control
over the strategic borders, Greater Jerusalem, settlements, water
resources and key roads in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu dubbed his proposal as the "Allon-Plus plan" -- an
enlarged version of the original formula proposed by late Israeli
Foreign Minister Yigal Allon after the 1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Qurie, speaker of the Palestinian Council, also rejected
the plan. "This is not a basis for negotiations on a final
agreement," said Qurie, who played a major role in the Oslo
accords.
</P>
<P>
"The three prerequisites for peace were solution of the Arab
refugee problem, termination of the Israeli occupation that began
in 1967, and definition of the nature of the relations between
Israelis and Palestinians, in particular, with the Arabs, in
general," he said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister's Office said Netanyahu's plan was
based on what he thought to be "a broad consensus that exists
within the Israeli public" and was aimed at gaining popular
support in the nation.
</P>
<P>
But PNA Cabinet Secretary-General Ahmed Abdel Rahman said
Netanyahu's plan was meant to suppress and terrorize the
Palestinian people in Jerusalem. PNA Finance Minister Mohammed
Nashashibi said the "Allon-plus plan" smacks of Nazi ideology and
reflects Hitler's belief on national security.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu plan was similar to the detailed map on final
settlement disclosed by the Hebrew press last Thursday, in which
Israel will retain over 60 percent of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
This is much less than the 90 percent required by the PNA,
which hopes to establish an independent state with East
Jerusalem as capital in the final arrangements. Israel's current
hardline government has ruled out the redivision of Jerusalem
and establishment of a Palestinian state alongside the Jewish
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Carrying Out Re-employment Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- More laid-off workers are getting
new jobs in Beijing with help from the re-employment project.
</P>
<P>
The project consists of four programs: job introduction,
professional skill training, social insurance and labor service
companies.
</P>
<P>
The project was carried out last year, with more than 20,000
laid-off workers finding new jobs through 239 job introduction
agencies and more than 200 job introduction fairs.
</P>
<P>
Professional skill training played an important part in helping
people find jobs. A labour force of more than 80,000 people
received training last year, and 80 percent of them found
employment.
</P>
<P>
The rapid development of labor-service enterprises has provided
more employment opportunities, helping 20,100 people find jobs
last year, and this year the industry is expected to provide more
than 50,000 job positions.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment insurance system provides basic guarantees for
laid offs' lives. An unemployment relief fund of 11.43 million
yuan (about 1.1 million US dollars) was offered to 11,150 laid-off
workers last year.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government's goal is to help more than 60 percent
laid-off workers get reemployed this year, and keep the registered
unemployment rate below two percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
