<HEADLINE> Submarine Cable System to Link Africa by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Liu Yegang)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 5 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has signed
memorandums of understanding with three other African countries
in the first step towards establishing South-Western Africa
submarine cable system.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's major telecommunication company, TELKOM, signed
the agreement with Gabon, Ghana and Senegal, the company
announced here yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Local daily "Business Day" today quoted a TELKOM spokesman as
saying that the agreements were the first step in studying the
feasibility of an integrated South-Western Africa submarine cable
system.
</P>
<P>
The system, known as SAT-3/WASC or African Atlantic
Telephony/West African Submarine Cable, will be routed along the
West African coastline between Senegal and Cape Town, with
landings in a number of African countries en route.
</P>
<P>
The system could provide connectivity to more than 35
sub-Saharan African countries, of which 16 will be via direct
submarine cable connections.
</P>
<P>
At least four more Western and Southern African operators will
sign memorandums with TELKOM within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
The SAT-3/WASC system is ready for commercial service by
mid-2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
