<HEADLINE> Japanese Troupe to Stage Women War Victims in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Bunkaza Troupe will stage
a three-act drama based on "Sandakan Brothel No. 8" in the Beijing
Theatre on June 21 and 22, to mark the 25th anniversary of the
normalization of diplomatic relations between Japan and China.
</P>
<P>
"Sandakan Brothel No.8 -- An Introduction to the History of
Women at the Lowest Level of Japanese Society" was a report
written by Japanese writer Tomoko Yamazaki in 1972. It described
miserable life of under-age women who were sold abroad to be
prostitutes by Japanese militarists who tried to allocate money
for war at the beginning of this century.
</P>
<P>
"Sandakan Brothel No.8" unveiled crimes Japanese militarists
committed toward the world people including Japanese during the
war. It was adapted into both a movie and a drama in
mid-1970s. The movie was introduced to China in 1979.
</P>
<P>
"Sandakan Brothel No.8" attracted attention again recently when
the issue of "comfort women" has been made public.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Bunkaza Troupe was established in 1942. Mitsue
Suzuki directs the drama and plays the leading role of Saki.
</P>
<P>
Tomoko Yamazaki will visit China with the Troupe. "Sandakan
Brothel No.8" (Chinese version) will also be published at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
The activity was sponsored by the Chinese Association for
Cultural Exchange with Foreign Countries, China Performing Arts
Agency, and the Japanese Pan-Asia Cultural Exchange Center. It
also received support from the Chinese Ministry of Culture and
Agency for Cultural Affairs of the Japanese Ministry of Education.
</P>
<P>
The Troupe also plans to give performances in northeast China's
cities of Changchun and Dalian.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Delhi Tops in Air Pollution: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- With emission of nearly 1,400
tons of pollution everyday, New Delhi, capital of India, is the
most air polluted city in the country, said a latest study by
Indian industry and business circles.
</P>
<P>
The study is prepared for a conference entitled "cleaner air",
which is being held here today to mark the world environment day.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total pollution load in the capital, as much as
1,050 tons is caused by 2.8 million vehicles. The industrial
pollution emitted from three thermal power plants, a large number
of brick kilns and other industrial units amounts to roughly one
third of the total air pollution.
</P>
<P>
Bombay, with 650 tons of vehicle pollution load everyday, ranks
second to New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
The main pollutants emitted from automobiles are particulate
matter, sulfur dioxide, oxides of nitrogen, hydrocarbons and
carbon monoxide, the study said.
</P>
<P>
The study recommended a number of measures to combat air
pollution caused by vehicles such as enforcement of stricter
vehicular emission norms and use of cleaner fuels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
