<HEADLINE> Bulls Wins Second Match in NBA Final Series </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHICAGO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Chicago Bulls took a 2-0 lead
in the NBA final series with a 97-85 victory over Utah Jazz here
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Michael Jordan, the last-second hero of game one on Sunday,
finished just one assist shy of his first finals triple double
with 38 points, 13 rebounds and nine assists.
</P>
<P>
The victory means that the Bulls, seeking their fifth title in
seven years, go to Salt Lake City for the next three games in the
seven-game series with their home court advantage intact.
</P>
<P>
Even if the Jazz, whose formidable home record in the regular
season included a victory over Chicago, win all three games, they
would have to come back to Chicago and win at least once to close
out the series.
</P>
<P>
Only twice in NBA history has a team lost the first two games
of the finals and rallied to win the title. It was most recently
done by Portland in 1977.
</P>
<P>
Utah's NBA Most Valuable Player Karl Malone suffered a dreadful
night shooting, hitting only 6-of-20 field goal attempts. He
finished with 20 points.
</P>
<P>
Jeff Hornacek added 19 for the Jazz before he fouled out with
just over a minute left in the fourth quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
