<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ROUND-UP: United Africa to Develop Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Unite to meet challenges and
develop economy. This is the common stand reached by leaders of
African countries at the just concluded 33rd summit conference of
the Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
During the OAU summit from June 2 to 4, the African Economic
Community (AEC) was officially inaugurated by leaders of African
countries to promote the process of economic integration on the
continent.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the economies of African countries have
developed in an encouraging way with the improvement of political
environment on the continent, though there are still conflicts,
strifes and violences in some parts of the region.
</P>
<P>
Regional economic organizations, such as the East African
Cooperation, the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa
(COMESA), the Southern African Development Community (SADC), the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), have taken
measures to promote regional cooperation and economic integration
to jointly develop their economies.
</P>
<P>
In such an encouraging circumstance comes the establishment of
the African Economic Community that is geared to become a force
in ridding the continent of poverty and deprivation.
</P>
<P>
This move vindicates the belief of successive generations of
African leaders that Africa could never be independent unless it
took responsibility for its economic and political destiny.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, who is also the new OAU
executive chairman, said at the first AEC summit that the
establishment of the highest organ of the AEC constituted a
standard by which Africa's future economic policies would be
judged by Africans and outsiders.
</P>
<P>
The AEC takes regional integration bodies as its pillars. In this
way, African countries are joining together to respond to the fierce
challenges in the world economic arena.
</P>
<P>
The inauguration of the AEC shows the will of unity of African
countries in developing their economies, which will surely push
forward the economic progress in the continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian State Premier Defends Sydney Olympic Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- New South Wales state Premier Bob
Carr admitted Thursday the Sydney 2000 Olympic's site was a
"polluted and degraded industrial" area but vowed the Games would
be the greenest ever in Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
