<HEADLINE> 28 Nationalized Banks Involved in Swindle in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- More than 6,600 million rupees
(194.12 million U.S dollars) were swindled off by 28 nationalized
banks during the period between March 1993 and March 1996,
according to a recent internal report of the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister's office is reported to have asked all the
investigating agencies to look into the various scams and submit a
status report at the earliest. These developments followed the CRB
Group scam in which several hundred crores of public money were
swindled.
</P>
<P>
The country's Punjab National Bank (PNB) tops the list of banks
involved in scams. As many as 269 cases were registered against
the bank which has swindled more than 560 million rupees (16.47
million dollars). The second on the list is the State Bank of
India (SBI) against which as many as 1,868 cases were filed and
the amount of money involved is more than 490 million rupees
(14.41 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The report also states that 77 cases were registered against
Indian nationalized banks in foreign countries and the money
swindled was about 600 million rupees (17.65 million dollars). The
Bank of India heads the list with scams involving almost 530
million rupees (15.59 million dollars) in various countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
