<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition Concerned Over Indians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dhaka, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Leader of the Bangladesh Nationalist
Party (BNP) khaleda Zia has expressed concern over some reported
activities by some Indians inside Bangladeshi territory, the local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Quoting news reports on landing of an Indian helicopter at a
village in Habiganj, the former prime minister claimed all its
passengers were military personnel, but the government is yet to
give any explanation or formally protest it.
</P>
<P>
"It is an unholy and dangerous exercise that a foreign fighter
could safely intrude into our airspace, safely landed, stayed and
took off without obstruction," the opposition leader told a
function marking the 12th anniversary of the daily Inqilab, an
influential newspaper, Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zia also suspected that an agreement giving a corridor to India
might have been signed.
</P>
<P>
She mentioned a recent meeting of some Indian officials with
the divisional commissioner of northern Mymensingh, noting that
the officials came by road through the Haluaghat border and
returned by the same way.
</P>
<P>
"Naturally, it raises the question whether the agreement to
give a corridor to India has already been signed," the BNP
chairperson said.
</P>
<P>
The opposition leader has been accusing the government of
selling out state sovereignty to India.
</P>
<P>
Zia expressed her deep concern at those news reports and over
the silence of the government. "The government has neither given
any explanation nor protested the news items regarding the
security-related matters," she added.  
</P>
