<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Tamil Rebels Shut Camp in North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Liberation Tigers
of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) has shut its camp in the north, fleeing from
advancing government troops in a major operation "Jaya Sikuru"
(Certain Victory) launched on May 13.
</P>
<P>
According to military sources today, the LTTE Wednesday closed
down its camp north of Omanthai, a rebel-held town which was
overrun by government troops last week, in Northern Province.
</P>
<P>
The troops, whose target is to capture 75 kilometers of highway
on the main south-north road to open a supply line to the Jaffna
Peninsula, are now moving steadily from the newly recaptured town
of Nedunkerni, dismantling several rebel bunkers.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest reports, the LTTE high command has
ordered the dismantling of more camps while the troops have
attacked several rebel positions backed by air cover and destroyed
a number of rebel strongholds.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the rebels have sabotaged a transformer at
Oddamavadi in Vallaichchenai, interrupting power supply in the
area.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting a guerrilla war against the Sri
Lankan government since 1983 for a separate state in the country.
</P>
<P>
