<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Grants Privileges to Foreign Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Romania will soon provide more
privileges to overseas investors to add momentum to the growing
capital influx to the country.
</P>
<P>
The government passed a urgent amendment to current foreign
investment laws today, granting preferential taxes and tariffs to
big overseas investors and those who invest in infrastructure, the
environment and in less-developed areas.
</P>
<P>
Entrepreneurs who invest over 350,000 U.S. dollars or whose
products are mostly sold abroad will be exempted from income tax
and import tariffs.
</P>
<P>
The decree also allows foreign investors to send their foreign
currency incomes abroad and bans nationalization and requisition
of foreign ventures which abide by Romanian tax regulations.
</P>
<P>
Overseas buyers of Romanian company stocks will pay a lower
profit tax of one percent.
</P>
<P>
The parliament passed a new rule earlier this year allowing the
investors to buy land for their projects.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment is surging since the country endorsed the
Foreign Investment Law in 1991. The Netherlands leads investors
with 264 million dollars, followed by South Korea and
Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Gov't Agencies Urged to Buy Local Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's national car "Timor"
has been official sedan for government officials and state
company executives since April, a cabinet minister said.
</P>
<P>
State Minister for National Development Planning Ginandjar
Kartasasmita said here last night that "for this year, the
budgetary directives include a ruling that if government offices
need passenger cars for official use, they must buy national cars,
which is the Timor sedan," Ginandjar said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, Minister of Industry and Trade Tunky Ariwibowo
said government offices and state-owned firms would soon be
required to buy Timor sedans to prop up the national car's
slumping sales.
</P>
<P>
But Ginandjar said that the ruling had already taken effect
with the beginning of this 1997/98 fiscal year from April 1.
</P>
<P>
Ginandjar said the ruling was based on the understanding that
the government -- which included state firms owned by provincial
and regional administrations -- should naturally support a
national program it had designed.
</P>
<P>
The national car program, launched in February 1996, grants
tariff and luxury sales tax exemptions to national cars on
condition that their local content rises to 60 percent in three
years.
</P>
<P>
However, only a joint venture between Pt. Timor Putra Nasional
and South Korean Kia Motors is qualified to produce national cars
until 1999.
</P>
<P>
Japan and the European Union have taken Indonesia's national
car policy to the World Trade Organization's dispute settlement
body.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
