<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pollution in Nepali Capital Hazardous to Health: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Air and noise pollution in some
areas of this capital city of Nepal is significantly high with
possible health risks to local residents, a Nepali institute said
today.
</P>
<P>
A recent study in Kathmandu found that the level of dust
concentration in the air is 1,053 micro-grams per cubic meter,
over four times the acceptable level set by the World Health
Organization (WHO), according to the Nepal Environment and
Scientific Services (NESS).
</P>
<P>
Under the WHO air quality guidelines, the acceptable level is
230 micro-grams per cubic meter for suspended particles, the NESS
said in its study report made public here today.
</P>
<P>
The risky level of dust in the air may cause some health
hazards like common cold, cough, asthma. Sore throats and
bronchitis, it said.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, the noise levels at some places in the Kathmandu
Valley range from 63 to 76 decibel, the NESS study said, adding
that 60 decibel of noise could be harmful for health.
</P>
<P>
The study cited the increasing number of vehicles, unnecessary
honking of vehicles, poor road condition and lack of noise control
regulations as main causes of the high noise pollution level in
the city.
</P>
<P>
It also found that the Bagmati, a major river runs through
Kathmandu, has become a "sewage" as some 95 percent of its flow
comes from the toilets of local houses.
</P>
<P>
NESS researchers in their report suggested that the government
should take effective policy and regulatory measures to control
the worsening pollution situation in the capital.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
