<HEADLINE> South Korea, Kyrgyzstan Agree to Expand Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 4 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Young-sam
and visiting Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev agreed today to expand
bilateral ties in trade and investment, when they met here.
</P>
<P>
Akayev, the first Kyrgyz president to visit South Korea since
it established formal relations with Seoul in 1992, arrived here
Tuesday for a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
In their talks, Akayev said he hoped South Korean businesses
would make active investment in Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
In turn, Kim asked for Kyrgyz government's support to
facilitate Korean firms' investment in the Central Asian country,
Presidential aides said.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents agreed that Seoul would extend an economic
development cooperation fund (EDCF) loan for Kyrgyzstan to develop
a telecommunication modernization project, and train personnel in
scientific and technological fields.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed on setting up a panel of businessmen to
promote cooperation between the two countries' private economic
sectors.
</P>
<P>
Kim and Akayev expressed satisfaction at the conclusion of a
cultural agreement and the initialing of an investment guarantee
accord, reached during their talks. whose two-way trade stood at
6.07 billion U.S. dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
After the summit talks, the two leaders signed a joint
declaration on the principles of friendship and cooperation, which
sets guidelines for strengthening bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The declaration calls for the two countries to promote mutual
investment and the establishment of joint ventures and financial
institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
