<HEADLINE> Lukashenko's Order Implements Russian-Belarusian Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Belarusian President Alexandr
Lukashenko has issued a special order in Minsk, the capital of
Belarus, to implement the Russian-Belarusian Union Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko said the implementation of the treaty was the
uppermost task of the nation, Itar-Tass said today.
</P>
<P>
In the order, the president asked relevant authorities to
formulate draft programs, including a fight against organized
crime, and the national defense of the Commonwealth of Independent
States, before August.
</P>
<P>
The Russian-Belarusian Union Treaty, signed by Russian
President Boris Yeltsin and Lukashenko on May 23, included
concrete measures to integrate, to an extent, the former Soviet
republics.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Yeltsin said the two nations might establish an
integral monetary system. Lukashenko once expressed opposition to
such a system, saying it would have a negative impact on the
Belarusian economy by devaluing its ruble. 
