<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Not Fully Ready for Finance Liberalization: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has not been ready for
full liberalization of its financial sector, as the country
currently sees some competitive disadvantages in the sector, Thai
Commerce Minister Narongchai Akrasanee said.
</P>
<P>
The minister made this remark here on Tuesday in response to
pressure from the US government which is pushing Thailand to open
its financial sector to foreign financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
However, Narongchai said that Thailand would cooperate with all
members of the World Trade Organization (WTO) to work out steps
for future liberalization of the finance sector.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has a timetable for that, which will be followed
strictly, he was quoted as saying by local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the US government reportedly sent a letter to Thai
Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Amnuay Virawan, calling
for Thailand to allow foreign financial institutions to freely
engage in various financial businesses in the country.
</P>
<P>
It also urged the Thai government to guarantee the security of
foreign investment in the sector, or at least to grant privileges
under the most-favored-nation framework for business expansion in
the sector.
</P>
<P>
However, Amnuay replied that no developing country could accede
to such requests due to the big competitiveness gap with the U.S..
</P>
<P>
The WTO reportedly will be receiving the financial
liberalization commitments and timetables from all of its members
by December this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
