<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Calls for Institutional Reform of OAS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican Foreign Minister
Fernando Naranjo called for institutional reform of the
Organization of American States (OAS) and reaffirmed his country's
support for the integration process of the Americas, the Foreign
Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
"The OAS' biggest challenge on its 50th anniversary is centered
on the building of a new institutional system for the Americas
today, based on new regional and world realities and vis-a-vis the
responsibilities of the next century," Naranjo told the General
Assembly of the OAS.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly is holding a plenary session in Lima, Peru.
</P>
<P>
The growing importance of trade and the integration of
financial systems, among others, require a new institutional
system in the Americas, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the system "should be the engine for the development of
our peoples."
</P>
<P>
He criticized the lack of cooperation in the war against drug
trafficking and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"Drug trafficking and terrorism have reached the extremes of
incredible despicableness in its practices. We can confront it
with success only when we join together through actions of
solidarity," he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister stressed the importance of sustainable
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"The planning of the future with a hemispherical sense
requires, necessarily, national development and the conservation
of the resources found in the Americas," he said.
</P>
<P>
Naranjo ratified the Inter-American Convention against
Corruption in Lima today.
</P>
<P>
The objectives of this convention are to promote the
development of nations and facilitate cooperation among member
states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
