<HEADLINE> Four Countries Act to Protect Caribbean Reefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Mexico,
Guatemala, Honduras and Belize will sign an agreement on Thursday
to protect the coral reefs shared by the four countries in the
Caribbean Sea.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will be signed by the Mexican, Guatemalan and
Honduran presidents and the prime minister of Belize, at
southeastern Mexico's Mayan site. The accord aims at consolidating
tourist development and fishing opportunities in the region.
</P>
<P>
Protection of reefs will extend from the Yucatan peninsula in
Mexico to Roatan Island in Honduras, and include the coastlines of
Belize and Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
The Caribbean barrier reef of the four countries, which
stretches for 1000 kilometers, is the second longest in the world
after Australia's Great Barrier Reef.
</P>
<P>
The coral reefs of the Caribbean are the home to thousands of
marine species that need protection, and are a barrier which
diminishes the force of waves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
