<HEADLINE> Albanian President Narrowly Escapes Grenade Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- A hand grenade was flung at Albanian
President Sali Berisha this afternoon but failed to blow up, when
he was campaigning at a mass rally for the upcoming general
elections in the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
Berisha, campaigning on behalf of his Democratic Party, was
speaking at the village of Shkallnur of the Durres district, about
40 kilometers west of Tirana at some 6:00 p.m. local time, when a
young man threw a grenade at him from about 15 meters away.
</P>
<P>
The Albania state TV showed that the grenade missed Berisha and
bounced off a door behind him. A suspect, later identified as Ilir
Ceta, 26, was captured on the spot.
</P>
<P>
In a TV speech this evening, Berisha condemned the attempt as
an ugly terrorist act aimed to take the lives of as many people as
possible.
</P>
<P>
As the general elections slated on June 29 are nearing, the
situation in Albania has been worsening again with explosions and
terrorist activities rife. 20 people were wounded Monday in a
powerful blast in a Tirana cafe.
</P>
<P>
The general elections were called after Albania was engulfed by
riots earlier this year caused by the collapse of shady investment
schemes, in which thousands of Albanians lost their money.
</P>
<P>
A 6500-strong Italian-led multinational force approved by the
United Nations was deployed in Albania after 500 people were
reportedly in the nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
