<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Grottos Near Dunhuang Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Two grottos near the Mogao Grottos
in Dunhuang City, northwest China's Gansu Province, opened to the
public recently.
</P>
<P>
The Yulin Grottos, which are 176 km from Dunhuang, have 42
caves with more than 1,000 sq.m. of wall paintings and Buddhist
sculptures dating back to the Northern Wei Dynasty (386-534) and
the Yuan (1271-1368).
</P>
<P>
They were among the first group of cultural relics to be given
state protection in 1961, but were closed to the public owing to
difficulties in getting there until a road was completed recently.
</P>
<P>
Visitors to the grottos, no matter from at home or overseas,
can visit the exquisite grottos after paying 40 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Another grotto opened recently at the Western Thousand-Buddha
Cave some 35 km to the southwest of Dunhuang. It has 19 caves
built from the Northern Wei to the Tang Dynasty (618-907). 
</P>
</TEXT>
