<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United Opposition Taking Shape in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A united opposition party is taking
shape in the Philippines as four opposition parties have finally
agreed to merge and field a common candidate for the 1998
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The four parties, after negotiations, agreed Wednesday to
formally launch the United Opposition on June 11, on the eve of
the country's commemoration of Independence Day, the Manila Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The United Opposition will include the Partido ng Masang
Pilipino party (PMP), Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino (Laban), the
People's Reform Party (PRP) and the Nationalist People's
Coalition, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The four parties also decided to select a common candidate
against the formidable ruling Lakas-NUCD party in the 1998 polls.
They gave up the traditional convention-type selection, and
instead adopted a new method under which all presidential hopefuls
will have an equal and fair chance to be nominated.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Joseph Estrada of the PMP, Senator Edgardo
Angara of Laban and Miriam Defensor-Santiago of PRP are the main
aspirants for the Presidency in the opposition bloc.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough of unifying the four parties came at the heel
of Estrada's resignation Wednesday as the chairman of the
Presidential Anti-Crime Commission. By taking the move, Estrada
severed all ties with the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Lakas-NUCD party immediately scoffed at the future
of the proposed United Opposition, calling it a "transient and a
fleeting arrangement". 
</P>
</TEXT>
