<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAS Backs Argentina's Peaceful Solution to Malvinas Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The 27th General Assembly of the
Organization of American States (OAS) has expressed its support
for Argentina's way to seek a peaceful solution to the dispute
over the Malvina (Falkland) Islands dispute.
</P>
<P>
The assembly being held in Lima approved a statement on the
question of the Malvina Islands whose sovereignty remains a source
of controversy between Argentina and Britain.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that in 1988 the OAS asked the governments
of Argentina and Britain to resume negotiations and come up with a
peaceful solution to the sovereignty dispute as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The OAS assembly expressed satisfaction with the reaffirmation
of Argentina's willingness to continue exploring all possible ways
to a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the OAS has decided to continue
examining the question until a definitive solution is reached.
</P>
<P>
Before the statement was approved, Martinez Rios, the
representative for Argentina, said that the recovery of the
Malvina Islands is of great significance for the people and
government of his country.
</P>
<P>
He said that Britain has not responded in a positive way to
Argentina's willingness to resume dialogue on the Malvinas issue.
</P>
<P>
He declared that Argentina remains convinced that only
negotiations can lead to a resolution of this matter.
</P>
<P>
Argentina's position is backed by several OAS member countries,
including Paraguay, Ecuador, Peru, Chile, Venezuela and Brazil,
whose representatives agreed on the need for Argentina and Britain
to resume talks to solve the controversy over the islands.
</P>
<P>
Argentina and Britain began to fight in April 1982 for the
sovereignty of the islands, which located to the east of the
strait of Magellan in South America and 550 kilometers off the
east coast of Argentina. In June, Britain regained control over
the islands. Since then the United Nations General Assembly has
asked the two countries to negotiate on the dispute. But they have
failed to reach any agreement on the issue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
