<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soil Erosion Control Efforts Paid-off along Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 5 (Xinhua) -- China's eight years of soil
erosion control efforts along the upper branch of the Yangtze
River have reaped some positive results, with marked improvement
in the regional ecological environment and the local residents'
quality of life.
</P>
<P>
According to a recently-closed working meeting on soil erosion
control, a total of 630 million yuan (nearly 80 million US
dollars) has been spent on the work over the past eight years,
putting 45,800 sq km of eroded land under control.
</P>
<P>
In addition to an ecological forest, nearly 460,000 ha of fruit
trees and other trees grown for special economic purposes have
been planted along the upper branch of Yangtze River, which
includes seven provinces and Chongqing municipality, according to
a source from the conference.
</P>
<P>
In Xihe County of northwest China's Gansu province, the soil
erosion control effort has helped to increase the per capita grain
output by 22 percent and helped 150,000 people shed poverty.
</P>
<P>
The projects centering on the upper branch of the Yangtze began
in 1988, when experts estimated that 35 percent of the total land
area in the region suffered from soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
The program also plays a key role in checking sand silting in
the Yangtze River. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Operation Under Way To Clean Up Pearl River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Pearl River, south China's main
water system and supplier of 80 percent of Hong Kong's drinking
and industrial water, is expected to have the quality of its water
further improved to meet higher standards.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Forestry has vowed to consolidate the
ecological environment in the area by speeding up construction of
the Pearl River Shelter Forestry Project in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
The Guangdong provincial government also plans to renovate
polluting industries along the river and other waters, calling it
a "clean-water plan", today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
With efforts made in the last two years, half the Pearl River
water is now drinkable and usable, compared with a rate of some 30
percent in 1995, according to a new national environment
communique.
</P>
<P>
But with forestry coverage decreasing along the Pearl River,
water and soil erosion is serious, and water is deteriorating,
said Li Shidong, an official with the Ministry of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry vowed annual increases in its investment in the
Pearl River Shelter Forestry Project as Hong Kong returns to its
motherland, aiming to improve the fragile ecological environment
of the area.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurated last year, the project is one of the ministry's 10
big ecological projects.
</P>
<P>
It involves 177 cities and counties in Guangdong, Yunnan and
Guizhou provinces, and Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region. When the
first phase is completed in 2010, 1.2 million hectares of forests
will be added to the region, bringing the forestry coverage rate
from 35 percent to almost 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
"South China and especially Hong Kong will greatly benefit from
the ecological improvement," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Budgeted at 480 million yuan (57.8 million US dollars), the
project is on a trial basis in 13 counties with a two million yuan
(240,000 dollars) central government investment last year.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Forestry plans to put five million yuan
(602,000 dollars) into the project this year. Provincial and local
governments will contribute an equal amount of money.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
