<HEADLINE> Shanghai Residents Regard Pollution Human's First Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- A survey has found that 42 percent
of Shanghai residents regard pollution as the biggest problem mankind
will have to tackle in the next century.
</P>
<P>
In line behind that are energy and population woes, according
to the survey conducted last month by "Xinwen Bao" (News Daily)
and a survey company in the city.
</P>
<P>
Some 69.5 percent of the respondents said that coordinated
efforts are to be made in achieving economic as well as
environment development, and 24.7 percent noted that environmental
protection should outweigh economic development.
</P>
<P>
Many Shanghai residents are not satisfied with the condition of
their environment, complaining about air pollution, limited green
space, polluted water and noise, the survey indicates.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the citizens' lack of environmental awareness
had become the major factor to hinder Shanghai's drive for
modernization. 
</P>
