<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Chinese Revolutionary Area Becomes Grain Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The once harsh and adverse conditions
of the Loess Plateau of northwest China's Shaanxi province have
been conquered at a number of successful grain production bases.
</P>
<P>
The three prefectures and cities of Yulin, Yan'an, and
Tongchuan -- all former Chinese revolutionary bases in northern
Shaanxi -- produced 2.5 billion kg of grain last year, with the
average per-ha of maize output reaching 6,090 kg, 1,890 kg more
than the provincial average.
</P>
<P>
The area is rich in land resources, accounting for 56 percent of
the province's total farmland. But random reclamation worsened the
eco-system, and as a result local people lived a meager life for
many years.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1980s, Yan'an began to develop ecological
agriculture by reclaiming forest areas from farmland and growing
high-profit forests instead to improve the environment and promote
diversified management.
</P>
<P>
The city has built about 86,000 ha of high-quality apple yards,
and its forest coverage rate has risen to 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
The sandy Yulin Prefecture has basically fixed its 570,000 ha
of quicksand area, and cultivated nearly 100,000 ha of high-yield
farmland out of it, with 12,000 kg of per-ha grain output.
</P>
<P>
Yan'an and Yulin alone are expected to produce three billion kg
of grain by the end of the century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0280 </DOCNO>
