<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Study Finds no Link Between Gulf War, Birth Defects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Results of a U.S. study
published today show that the Gulf War veterans face no unusual
risk of having babies with birth defects as some have feared.
</P>
<P>
The study reviewed the records of more than 75,000 newborns
from 1991 through 1993, finding that the number of birth defects
among war veterans' children was virtually the same as the risk
among civilians.
</P>
<P>
The results of the study, conducted by the Walter Reed Army
Institute of Research, were published in today's issue of the New
England of Journal.
</P>
<P>
Many Gulf War veterans have complained of a variety of
unexplained symptoms, including fatigue, diarrhea, memory problems
and trouble sleeping.
</P>
<P>
Some also worry that their war exposure harmed their
reproductive health, making them more likely to have babies with
serious birth defects.
</P>
<P>
The study found that 1.9 percent of Gulf War veterans' babies
had severe birth defects, identical to the number among veterans
who did not serve in the Gulf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big US Auto Makers to Build Ethanol-Burning Vehicles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 4 (Xinhua) -- The Ford Motor Company, the No. 2
American auto maker, announced Tuesday that it would begin
building 250,000 cars, mini-vans and pickup trucks annually that
can burn ethanol or gasoline.
</P>
<P>
The decision was described by the New York Times in a report
today as "the largest alternative fuel program in the United
States since the oil crises of the 1970's produced alarm about
American reliance on imported oil."
</P>
<P>
Ford officials characterized their announcement as part of a
corporate commitment to clean air. The company hoped that the
sharp increase in the availability of ethanol-burning vehicles
would prompt more service stations to sell the fuel. Ford last
year produced just 5,000 such vehicles. Only 40 stations across
the country currently sell ethanol, which is grain-based alcohol
mixed with a little gasoline.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Chrysler, th No. 3 auto maker in this
country, is expected to announce a similar program next week, and
General Motors, the No. one auto maker, is considering whether to
follow Ford and Chrysler's examples. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
