<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ruehe Expects Bonn to Decide on Eurofighter in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 4 (Xinhua) -- German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe
said today that he expected the Bonn government to decide on the
purchase of Eurofighter 2000 before Summer recess in July.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters after meeting with his British counterpart
George Robertson at the exclusive military zone of Cologne/Bonn
airport that the cabinet might make the decision at a budget
meeting on July 11.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with Robertson, Ruehe also voiced optimism
over a government decision in favor of buying the controversial
warplane while admitting that the financial difficulties facing
Bonn has made the deal more difficult.
</P>
<P>
Bonn is battling to meet the strict budget deficit and debt
limits required for joining the single European currency, the
euro, which is due to be launched from 1999. There remain doubts
over how to pay for the much-delayed Eurofighter.
</P>
<P>
Robertson, taking office in May after the Labour Party won the
British elections, stressed in the talks the continued interest of
the London government in the Eurofighter, saying London expected
serial production of the aircraft could start as early as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Britain, Italy and Spain have already approved the Eurofighter.
London plans to buy 232 Eurofighters, Rome 121 and Madrid 87. The
German armed forces intends to buy 180. The total price for the
four-nation project is estimated at over 65 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Germany's aerospace industry today urged a quick
government decision on the issue. Hans Eberhard Burke, head of
Germany's aerospace lobby (BDLI), said in Bonn that if the
government again delayed its decision on the Eurofighter in July,
German firms involved in the project would cease financing
preparatory work for production.
</P>
<P>
The main German firm involved is Daimler-Benz Aerospace (DASA).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece: Climate of Trust Necessary for Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Greece today stressed the need of
cultivating "a climate of calm and trust" before the start of
direct talks between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities,
government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said.
</P>
<P>
The direct talks between Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides and
Turkish-Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash will be held in New York
within the framework of efforts by U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan to seek a solution to Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Reppas said he hoped that the forthcoming direct talks would be
"fruitful."
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that Nicosia was contacting international
organizations charging that certain powers were trying to
undermine efforts for a Cyprus solution.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
"invaded" and occupied the northern third of the island in
response to a coup in Cyprus engineered by the junta then ruling
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The international communities have tried over the past 20 years
to find ways of resolving the Cyprus problem, but no progress have
been made so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Names Holbrooke New Cyprus Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 4 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Wednesday appointed high-profile diplomat Richard Holbrooke as
ambassador to Cyprus, signaling his administration's intention to
mediate for the settlement of an intractable dispute on the island
state.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by State Department spokesman
Nicholas Burns when he told reporters: "President Clinton has
named Ambassador Richard Holbrooke as the new U.S. special
presidential emissary on Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
"This appointment of one of our most capable negotiators
demonstrates our commitment to help promote a final political
settlement on Cyprus," Burns said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke will replace Richard Beattie, named by Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright last month as her adviser on
incorporating three foreign affairs agencies into the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been unofficially partitioned since Turkish troops
invaded the island in 1974 in response to a pro-Greek coup.
</P>
<P>
In 1983, Turkish Cypriots, who account for about a quarter of
the island's 750,000 people, declared a breakaway state in the
north under the protection of 30,000 Turkish troops. The
international community except for Turkey does not recognize the
breakaway state.
</P>
<P>
Burns said the appointment of Holbrooke represented a "rebirth
and a renewal" of the U.S. mediation effort between the Greek and
Turkish communities on the island, but he expected no "imminent
breakthrough" in the settlement of disputes, which has put Greece
and Turkey, the two NATO members close to war.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that President Glafkos Clerides of Cyprus and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktashwere due to meet in July in
New York and he said Washington strongly urged all parties to work
for a comprehensive, permanent settlement on the island.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, 55, is well-known for his role in negotiating the
Dayton peace accords that ended a three-year civil war in
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Approves Renewal of Iraqi Oil Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 4 (xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council today approved the renewal of Iraqi "oil-for-food deal"
for another period of 180 days beginning on June 8, 1997.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted unanimously, the Security Council said
the renewal of the "oil-for-food deal" was aimed to alleviate the
humanitarian crisis in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The council reiterated the commitment of all member countries
to the sovereignty and the territorial integrity of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, Chinese Acting Permanent Representative to
UN Wang Xuexian pointed out that the final goal of the current
action was to lift all the sanctions against Iraq, which was the
only way to solve the humanitarian crisis facing the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under UN sanctions since it invaded Kuwait in
August 1990, which have resulted in severe shortage of food,
medicine and other civilian needs. The UN Security Council
adopted Resolution 986 in April 1995, allowing Iraq to export 2
billion U.S. dollars worth of oil over 180 days to purchase the
urgently needed civilian goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970605.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Entities to Form Joint Delegation to Brussels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, June 4 (Xinhua) -- Top officials of Bosnia's two
entities agreed on Wednesday to form a joint delegation to the
international conference on assisting Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The agreement came out of the meeting here between Edhem
Bicakcic, prime minister of the Muslim-Croat federation and his
counterpart form the Serb republic, Gojko Klickovic.
</P>
<P>
According to local press, Klickovic said that entities will
present some joint projects of reconstruction, specially those in
the fields of metallurgy and energy to the two-day donors'
conference which begins on June 24.
</P>
<P>
The conference is expected to raise some 1.4 billion dollars for
Bosnia's reconstruction this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
